<section id=3D"section-1">
      <h2 id=3D"name-introduction">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
" class=3D"section-number selfRef">1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-introduction" class=3D"section-name s=
elfRef">Introduction</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-1-1">
                JSON Schema is a JSON media type for defining the structure=
 of JSON data. JSON Schema
                is intended to define validation, documentation, hyperlink =
navigation, and interaction
                control of JSON data.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dra=
ft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-1-2">
                This specification defines JSON Schema core terminology and=
 mechanisms, including
                pointing to another JSON Schema by reference,
                dereferencing a JSON Schema reference,
                specifying the dialect being used,
                specifying a dialect's vocabulary requirements,
                and defining the expected output.<a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-1-3">
                Other specifications define the vocabularies that perform a=
ssertions about validation,
                linking, annotation, navigation, and interaction.<a href=3D=
"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1-3" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-2">
      <h2 id=3D"name-conventions-and-terminology">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-2=
" class=3D"section-number selfRef">2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-conventions-and-terminology" class=3D=
"section-name selfRef">Conventions and Terminology</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-2-1">
               =20

                The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHA=
LL NOT", "SHOULD",
                "SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this =
document are to be
                interpreted as described in <span><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC2119" class=3D"xref">RFC 2119</=
a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC21=
19" class=3D"xref">RFC2119</a>]</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/d=
raft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-2-2">
                The terms "JSON", "JSON text", "JSON value", "member", "ele=
ment", "object", "array",
                "number", "string", "boolean", "true", "false", and "null" =
in this document are to
                be interpreted as defined in <span><a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8259" class=3D"xref">RFC 8259<=
/a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8=
259" class=3D"xref">RFC8259</a>]</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/=
draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p=
>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-3">
      <h2 id=3D"name-overview">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-3=
" class=3D"section-number selfRef">3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-overview" class=3D"section-name selfR=
ef">Overview</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-3-1">
                This document proposes a new media type "application/schema=
+json" to identify a JSON
                Schema for describing JSON data.
                It also proposes a further optional media type, "applicatio=
n/schema-instance+json",
                to provide additional integration features.
                JSON Schemas are themselves JSON documents.
                This, and related specifications, define keywords allowing =
authors to describe JSON
                data in several ways.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dra=
ft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-3-2">
                JSON Schema uses keywords to assert constraints on JSON ins=
tances or annotate those
                instances with additional information.  Additional keywords=
 are used to apply
                assertions and annotations to more complex JSON data struct=
ures, or based on
                some sort of condition.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/d=
raft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-3-3">
                To facilitate re-use, keywords can be organized into vocabu=
laries. A vocabulary
                consists of a list of keywords, together with their syntax =
and semantics.
                A dialect is defined as a set of vocabularies and their req=
uired support
                identified in a meta-schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-3-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a=
></p>
<p id=3D"section-3-4">
                JSON Schema can be extended either by defining additional v=
ocabularies,
                or less formally by defining additional keywords outside of=
 any vocabulary.
                Unrecognized individual keywords simply have their values c=
ollected as annotations,
                while the behavior with respect to an unrecognized vocabula=
ry can be controlled
                when declaring which vocabularies are in use.<a href=3D"htt=
ps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-3-4" class=3D"p=
ilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-3-5">
                This document defines a core vocabulary that MUST be suppor=
ted by any
                implementation, and cannot be disabled.  Its keywords are e=
ach prefixed
                with a "$" character to emphasize their required nature.  T=
his vocabulary
                is essential to the functioning of the "application/schema+=
json" media
                type, and is used to bootstrap the loading of other vocabul=
aries.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-3-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-3-6">
                Additionally, this document defines a RECOMMENDED vocabular=
y of keywords
                for applying subschemas conditionally, and for applying sub=
schemas to
                the contents of objects and arrays.  Either this vocabulary=
 or one very
                much like it is required to write schemas for non-trivial J=
SON instances,
                whether those schemas are intended for assertion validation=
, annotation,
                or both.  While not part of the required core vocabulary, f=
or maximum
                interoperability this additional vocabulary is included in =
this document
                and its use is strongly encouraged.<a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-3-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-3-7">
                Further vocabularies for purposes such as structural valida=
tion or
                hypermedia annotation are defined in other documents.  Thes=
e other
                documents each define a dialect collecting the standard set=
s of
                vocabularies needed to write schemas for that document's pu=
rpose.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-3-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-4">
      <h2 id=3D"name-definitions">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-definitions" class=3D"section-name se=
lfRef">Definitions</a>
      </h2>
<section id=3D"section-4.1">
        <h3 id=3D"name-json-document">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-json-document" class=3D"section-n=
ame selfRef">JSON Document</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-4.1-1">
                    A JSON document is an information resource (series of o=
ctets) described by the
                    application/json media type.<a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.1-2">
                    In JSON Schema, the terms "JSON document", "JSON text",=
 and "JSON value" are
                    interchangeable because of the data model it defines.<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.1=
-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.1-3">
                    JSON Schema is only defined over JSON documents. Howeve=
r, any document or memory
                    structure that can be parsed into or processed accordin=
g to the JSON Schema data
                    model can be interpreted against a JSON Schema, includi=
ng media types like
                    <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/=
json-schema-core#RFC7049" class=3D"xref">CBOR</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC7049" class=3D"xref">RFC7049</=
a>]</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-cor=
e#section-4.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-4.2">
        <h3 id=3D"name-instance">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-instance" class=3D"section-name s=
elfRef">Instance</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-4.2-1">
                    A JSON document to which a schema is applied is known a=
s an "instance".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schem=
a-core#section-4.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.2-2">
                    JSON Schema is defined over "application/json" or compa=
tible documents,
                    including media types with the "+json" structured synta=
x suffix.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-4.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.2-3">
                    Among these, this specification defines the "applicatio=
n/schema-instance+json"
                    media type which defines handling for fragments in the =
URI.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-4.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-4.2.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-instance-data-model">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.2.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.2.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-instance-data-model" class=3D=
"section-name selfRef">Instance Data Model</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.1-1">
                        JSON Schema interprets documents according to a dat=
a model. A JSON value
                        interpreted according to this data model is called =
an "instance".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-=
core#section-4.2.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.1-2">
                        An instance has one of six primitive types, and a r=
ange of possible values
                        depending on the type:<a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<span class=3D"break"></span><dl class=3D"dlParallel" id=3D"section-4.2.1-3=
">
            <dt id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.1">null:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.2">A JSO=
N "null" value<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-=
core#section-4.2.1-3.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.3">boolean:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.4">A "tr=
ue" or "false" value, from the JSON "true" or "false" value<a href=3D"https=
://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.1-3.4" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.5">object:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.6">An un=
ordered set of properties mapping a string to an instance, from the JSON "o=
bject" value<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-4.2.1-3.6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.7">array:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.8">An or=
dered list of instances, from the JSON "array" value<a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.1-3.8" class=3D"pilc=
row">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.9">number:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.10">An a=
rbitrary-precision, base-10 decimal number value, from the JSON "number" va=
lue<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sectio=
n-4.2.1-3.10" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.11">string:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.2.1-3.12">A st=
ring of Unicode code points, from the JSON "string" value<a href=3D"https:/=
/json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.1-3.12" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
          <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
</dl>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.1-4">
                        Whitespace and formatting concerns, including diffe=
rent lexical
                        representations of numbers that are equal within th=
e data model, are thus
                        outside the scope of JSON Schema.  JSON Schema
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#vocabulary" class=3D"xref">vocabularies</a> (<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#vocabulary" clas=
s=3D"xref">Section 8.1</a>)</span> that wish
                        to work with such differences in lexical representa=
tions SHOULD define
                        keywords to precisely interpret formatted strings w=
ithin the data model
                        rather than relying on having the original JSON rep=
resentation Unicode
                        characters available.<a href=3D"https://json-schema=
.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.1-5">
                        Since an object cannot have two properties with the=
 same key, behavior for a
                        JSON document that tries to define two properties w=
ith
                        the same key in a single object is undefined.<a hre=
f=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.1-5=
" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.1-6">
                        Note that JSON Schema vocabularies are free to defi=
ne their own extended
                        type system.  This should not be confused with the =
core data model types
                        defined here.  As an example, "integer" is a reason=
able type for a
                        vocabulary to define as a value for a keyword, but =
the data model
                        makes no distinction between integers and other num=
bers.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-4.2.1-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-4.2.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-instance-equality">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.2.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.2.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-instance-equality" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">Instance Equality</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.2-1">
                        Two JSON instances are said to be equal if and only=
 if they are of the same type
                        and have the same value according to the data model=
. Specifically, this means:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12=
/json-schema-core#section-4.2.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-4.2.2-2.1">both are null; or<a h=
ref=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.2=
-2.1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-4.2.2-2.2">both are =
true; or<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
ection-4.2.2-2.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-4.2.2-2.3">both are =
false; or<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-4.2.2-2.3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-4.2.2-2.4">both are =
strings, and are the same codepoint-for-codepoint; or<a href=3D"https://jso=
n-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.2-2.4" class=3D"pil=
crow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-4.2.2-2.5">both are =
numbers, and have the same mathematical value; or<a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.2-2.5" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-4.2.2-2.6">both are =
arrays, and have an equal value item-for-item; or<a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.2-2.6" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-4.2.2-2.7">both are =
objects, and each property in one has exactly one property with
                                a key equal to the other's, and that other =
property has an equal
                                value.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dr=
aft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.2-2.7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a=
>
</li>
          </ul>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.2-3">
                        Implied in this definition is that arrays must be t=
he same length,
                        objects must have the same number of members,
                        properties in objects are unordered,
                        there is no way to define multiple properties with =
the same key,
                        and mere formatting differences (indentation, place=
ment of commas, trailing
                        zeros) are insignificant.<a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-4.2.3">
          <h4 id=3D"name-non-json-instances">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.2.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.2.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-non-json-instances" class=3D"=
section-name selfRef">Non-JSON Instances</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.3-1">
                        It is possible to use JSON Schema with a superset o=
f the JSON Schema data model,
                        where an instance may be outside any of the six JSO=
N data types.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-c=
ore#section-4.2.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.3-2">
                        In this case, annotations still apply; but most val=
idation keywords will not be useful,
                        as they will always pass or always fail.<a href=3D"=
https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.3-2" cla=
ss=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.2.3-3">
                        A custom vocabulary may define support for a supers=
et of the core data model.
                        The schema itself may only be expressible in this s=
uperset;
                        for example, to make use of the "const" keyword.<a =
href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.2.=
3-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
<div id=3D"schema-document">
<section id=3D"section-4.3">
        <h3 id=3D"name-json-schema-documents">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-json-schema-documents" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">JSON Schema Documents</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-4.3-1">
                    A JSON Schema document, or simply a schema, is a JSON d=
ocument used to describe
                    an instance.
                    A schema can itself be interpreted as an instance, but =
SHOULD always be given
                    the media type "application/schema+json" rather than
                    "application/schema-instance+json".  The "application/s=
chema+json" media
                    type is defined to offer a superset of the
                    fragment identifier syntax and semantics provided by
                    "application/schema-instance+json".<a href=3D"https://j=
son-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3-1" class=3D"pilcr=
ow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3-2">
                    A JSON Schema MUST be an object or a boolean.<a href=3D=
"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3-2" clas=
s=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-4.3.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-json-schema-objects-and-key">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.3.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.3.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-json-schema-objects-and-key" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">JSON Schema Objects and Keywords</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.1-1">
                        Object properties that are applied to the instance =
are called keywords,
                        or schema keywords.  Broadly speaking, keywords fal=
l into one
                        of five categories:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.o=
rg/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6=
</a></p>
<span class=3D"break"></span><dl class=3D"dlParallel" id=3D"section-4.3.1-2=
">
            <dt id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.1">identifiers:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.2">
                                control schema identification through setti=
ng a URI
                                for the schema and/or changing how the base=
 URI is determined<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sch=
ema-core#section-4.3.1-2.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.3">assertions:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.4">
                                produce a boolean result when applied to an=
 instance<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-4.3.1-2.4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.5">annotations:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.6">
                                attach information to an instance for appli=
cation use<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-4.3.1-2.6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.7">applicators:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.8">
                                apply one or more subschemas to a particula=
r location
                                in the instance, and combine or modify thei=
r results<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-4.3.1-2.8" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.9">reserved locations:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.3.1-2.10">
                                do not directly affect results, but reserve=
 a place
                                for a specific purpose to ensure interopera=
bility<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-4.3.1-2.10" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
          <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
</dl>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.1-3">
                        Keywords may fall into multiple categories, althoug=
h applicators
                        SHOULD only produce assertion results based on thei=
r subschemas'
                        results.  They should not define additional constra=
ints independent
                        of their subschemas.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.1-4">
                        Keywords which are properties within the same schem=
a object are referred to as adjacent keywords.<a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.1-5">
                        Extension keywords, meaning those defined outside o=
f this document
                        and its companions, are free to define other behavi=
ors as well.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-4.3.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.1-6">
                        A JSON Schema MAY contain properties which are not =
schema keywords.
                        Unknown keywords SHOULD be treated as annotations, =
where the value
                        of the keyword is the value of the annotation.<a hr=
ef=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.1-=
6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.1-7">
                        An empty schema is a JSON Schema with no properties=
, or only unknown
                        properties.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft=
/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.1-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-4.3.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-boolean-json-schemas">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.3.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.3.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-boolean-json-schemas" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">Boolean JSON Schemas</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.2-1">
                        The boolean schema values "true" and "false" are tr=
ivial schemas that
                        always produce themselves as assertion results, reg=
ardless of the
                        instance value.  They never produce annotation resu=
lts.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-4.3.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.2-2">
                        These boolean schemas exist to clarify schema autho=
r intent and
                        facilitate schema processing optimizations.  They b=
ehave identically
                        to the following schema objects (where "not" is par=
t of the
                        subschema application vocabulary defined in this do=
cument).<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
ection-4.3.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<span class=3D"break"></span><dl class=3D"dlParallel" id=3D"section-4.3.2-3=
">
            <dt id=3D"section-4.3.2-3.1">true:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.3.2-3.2">
                                Always passes validation, as if the empty s=
chema {}<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
ection-4.3.2-3.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
            <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-4.3.2-3.3">false:</dt>
            <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-4.3.2-3.4">
                                Always fails validation, as if the schema {=
 "not": {} }<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-4.3.2-3.4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
          <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
</dl>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.2-4">
                        While the empty schema object is unambiguous, there=
 are many
                        possible equivalents to the "false" schema.  Using =
the boolean
                        values ensures that the intent is clear to both hum=
an readers
                        and implementations.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-4.3.3">
          <h4 id=3D"name-schema-vocabularies">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.3.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.3.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-schema-vocabularies" class=3D=
"section-name selfRef">Schema Vocabularies</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.3-1">
                        A schema vocabulary, or simply a vocabulary, is a s=
et of keywords,
                        their syntax, and their semantics.  A vocabulary is=
 generally organized
                        around a particular purpose.  Different uses of JSO=
N Schema, such
                        as validation, hypermedia, or user interface genera=
tion, will
                        involve different sets of vocabularies.<a href=3D"h=
ttps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.3-1" clas=
s=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.3-2">
                        Vocabularies are the primary unit of re-use in JSON=
 Schema, as schema
                        authors can indicate what vocabularies are required=
 or optional in
                        order to process the schema.  Since vocabularies ar=
e identified by URIs
                        in the meta-schema, generic implementations can loa=
d extensions to support
                        previously unknown vocabularies.  While keywords ca=
n be supported outside
                        of any vocabulary, there is no analogous mechanism =
to indicate individual
                        keyword usage.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dr=
aft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a><=
/p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.3-3">
                        A schema vocabulary can be defined by anything from=
 an informal description
                        to a standards proposal, depending on the audience =
and interoperability
                        expectations.  In particular, in order to facilitat=
e vocabulary use within
                        non-public organizations, a vocabulary specificatio=
n need not be published
                        outside of its scope of use.<a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.3-3" class=3D"pilcro=
w">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-4.3.4">
          <h4 id=3D"name-meta-schemas">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.3.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.3.4. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-meta-schemas" class=3D"sectio=
n-name selfRef">Meta-Schemas</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.4-1">
                        A schema that itself describes a schema is called a=
 meta-schema.
                        Meta-schemas are used to validate JSON Schemas and =
specify which vocabularies
                        they are using.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/d=
raft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.4-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>=
</p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.4-2">
                        Typically, a meta-schema will specify a set of voca=
bularies, and validate
                        schemas that conform to the syntax of those vocabul=
aries.  However, meta-schemas
                        and vocabularies are separate in order to allow met=
a-schemas to validate
                        schema conformance more strictly or more loosely th=
an the vocabularies'
                        specifications call for.  Meta-schemas may also des=
cribe and validate
                        additional keywords that are not part of a formal v=
ocabulary.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-4.3.4-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<div id=3D"root">
<section id=3D"section-4.3.5">
          <h4 id=3D"name-root-schema-and-subschemas-">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4=
.3.5" class=3D"section-number selfRef">4.3.5. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-root-schema-and-subschemas-" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Root Schema and Subschemas and Resources</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.5-1">
                        A JSON Schema resource is a schema which is
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC6596" class=3D"xref">canonically</a> [<a href=3D"ht=
tps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC6596" class=3D"xref=
">RFC6596</a>]</span> identified by an
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">absolute URI</a> [<a href=3D"h=
ttps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xre=
f">RFC3986</a>]</span>.  Schema resources MAY
                        also be identified by URIs, including URIs with fra=
gments,
                        if the resulting secondary resource (as defined by
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">section 3.5 of RFC 3986</a> [<=
a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" c=
lass=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span>) is identical
                        to the primary resource.  This can occur with the e=
mpty fragment,
                        or when one schema resource is embedded in another.=
  Any such URIs
                        with fragments are considered to be non-canonical.<=
a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.=
3.5-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.5-2">
                        The root schema is the schema that comprises the en=
tire JSON document
                        in question.  The root schema is always a schema re=
source, where the
                        URI is determined as described in section
                        <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#initial-base" class=3D"xref">9.1.1</a>.
                        <span class=3D"cref">
                            Note that documents that embed schemas in anoth=
er format will not
                            have a root schema resource in this sense.  Exa=
ctly how such usages
                            fit with the JSON Schema document and resource =
concepts will be
                            clarified in a future draft.
            </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-4.3.5-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.5-3">
                        Some keywords take schemas themselves, allowing JSO=
N Schemas to be nested:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/jso=
n-schema-core#section-4.3.5-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-4.3.5-4">
<pre>
{
    "title": "root",
    "items": {
        "title": "array item"
    }
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-4.3.5-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.5-5">
                        In this example document, the schema titled "array =
item" is a subschema,
                        and the schema titled "root" is the root schema.<a =
href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-4.3.=
5-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.5-6">
                        As with the root schema, a subschema is either an o=
bject or a boolean.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-4.3.5-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.5-7">
                        As discussed in section
                        <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#id-keyword" class=3D"xref">8.2.1</a>, a JSON Schema document
                        can contain multiple JSON Schema resources.  When u=
sed without qualification,
                        the term "root schema" refers to the document's roo=
t schema.  In some
                        cases, resource root schemas are discussed.  A reso=
urce's root schema
                        is its top-level schema object, which would also be=
 a document root schema
                        if the resource were to be extracted to a standalon=
e JSON Schema document.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/jso=
n-schema-core#section-4.3.5-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-4.3.5-8">
                        Whether multiple schema resources are embedded or l=
inked with a reference,
                        they are processed in the same way, with the same a=
vailable behaviors.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-4.3.5-8" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
</section>
</div>
</section>
<div id=3D"fragments">
<section id=3D"section-5">
      <h2 id=3D"name-fragment-identifiers">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-5=
" class=3D"section-number selfRef">5. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-fragment-identifiers" class=3D"sectio=
n-name selfRef">Fragment Identifiers</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-5-1">
                In accordance with section 3.1 of <span><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC6839" class=3D"xref">RFC =
6839</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#RFC6839" class=3D"xref">RFC6839</a>]</span>,
                the syntax and semantics of fragment identifiers specified =
for
                any +json media type SHOULD be as specified for "applicatio=
n/json".
                (At publication of this document, there is no fragment iden=
tification
                syntax defined for "application/json".)<a href=3D"https://j=
son-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-5-1" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-5-2">
                Additionally, the "application/schema+json" media type supp=
orts two
                fragment identifier structures: plain names and JSON Pointe=
rs.
                The "application/schema-instance+json" media type supports =
one
                fragment identifier structure: JSON Pointers.<a href=3D"htt=
ps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-5-2" class=3D"p=
ilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-5-3">
                The use of JSON Pointers as URI fragment identifiers is des=
cribed in
                <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#RFC6901" class=3D"xref">RFC 6901</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC6901" class=3D"xref">RFC6901</=
a>]</span>.
                For "application/schema+json", which supports two fragment =
identifier syntaxes,
                fragment identifiers matching the JSON Pointer syntax, incl=
uding the empty string,
                MUST be interpreted as JSON Pointer fragment identifiers.<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-5-3=
" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-5-4">
                Per the W3C's
                <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#W3C.WD-fragid-best-practices-20121025" class=3D"xref">best pra=
ctices for fragment identifiers</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dra=
ft/2020-12/json-schema-core#W3C.WD-fragid-best-practices-20121025" class=3D=
"xref">W3C.WD-fragid-best-practices-20121025</a>]</span>,
                plain name fragment identifiers in "application/schema+json=
" are reserved for referencing
                locally named schemas.  All fragment identifiers that do
                not match the JSON Pointer syntax MUST be interpreted as
                plain name fragment identifiers.<a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-5-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-5-5">
                Defining and referencing a plain name fragment identifier w=
ithin an
                "application/schema+json" document are specified
                in the <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-=
12/json-schema-core#anchor" class=3D"xref">"$anchor" keyword</a> (<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#anchor" class=3D=
"xref">Section 8.2.2</a>)</span> section.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org=
/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-5-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></=
p>
<p id=3D"section-5-6"></p>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-6">
      <h2 id=3D"name-general-considerations">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6=
" class=3D"section-number selfRef">6. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-general-considerations" class=3D"sect=
ion-name selfRef">General Considerations</a>
      </h2>
<section id=3D"section-6.1">
        <h3 id=3D"name-range-of-json-values">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6=
.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">6.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-range-of-json-values" class=3D"se=
ction-name selfRef">Range of JSON Values</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-6.1-1">
                    An instance may be any valid JSON value as defined by <=
span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8=
259" class=3D"xref">JSON</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC8259" class=3D"xref">RFC8259</a>]</span>.
                    JSON Schema imposes no restrictions on type: JSON Schem=
a can describe any JSON
                    value, including, for example, null.<a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.1-1" class=3D"pilc=
row">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<div id=3D"language">
<section id=3D"section-6.2">
        <h3 id=3D"name-programming-language-indepe">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6=
.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">6.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-programming-language-indepe" clas=
s=3D"section-name selfRef">Programming Language Independence</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-6.2-1">
                    JSON Schema is programming language agnostic, and suppo=
rts the full range of
                    values described in the data model.
                    Be aware, however, that some languages and JSON parsers=
 may not be able to
                    represent in memory the full range of values describabl=
e by JSON.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-6.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"integers">
<section id=3D"section-6.3">
        <h3 id=3D"name-mathematical-integers">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6=
.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">6.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-mathematical-integers" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">Mathematical Integers</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-6.3-1">
                    Some programming languages and parsers use different in=
ternal representations
                    for floating point numbers than they do for integers.<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.3=
-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-6.3-2">
                    For consistency, integer JSON numbers SHOULD NOT be enc=
oded with a fractional
                    part.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/j=
son-schema-core#section-6.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"regex">
<section id=3D"section-6.4">
        <h3 id=3D"name-regular-expressions">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6=
.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">6.4. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-regular-expressions" class=3D"sec=
tion-name selfRef">Regular Expressions</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-6.4-1">
                    Keywords MAY use regular expressions to express constra=
ints, or constrain
                    the instance value to be a regular expression.
                    These regular expressions SHOULD be valid according to =
the regular expression
                    dialect described in <span><a href=3D"https://json-sche=
ma.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#ecma262" class=3D"xref">ECMA-262, sec=
tion 21.2.1</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sche=
ma-core#ecma262" class=3D"xref">ecma262</a>]</span>.<a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4-1" class=3D"pilcrow"=
>=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-6.4-2">
                    Regular expressions SHOULD be built with the "u" flag (=
or equivalent) to provide
                    Unicode support, or processed in such a way which provi=
des Unicode support as
                    defined by ECMA-262.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/=
draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a><=
/p>
<p id=3D"section-6.4-3">
                    Furthermore, given the high disparity in regular expres=
sion constructs support,
                    schema authors SHOULD limit themselves to the following=
 regular expression
                    tokens:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12=
/json-schema-core#section-6.4-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-6.4-4.1">individual Unicode char=
acters, as defined by the <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/20=
20-12/json-schema-core#RFC8259" class=3D"xref">JSON specification</a> [<a h=
ref=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8259" clas=
s=3D"xref">RFC8259</a>]</span>;<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/202=
0-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4-4.1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-6.4-4.2">simple charac=
ter classes ([abc]), range character classes ([a-z]);<a href=3D"https://jso=
n-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4-4.2" class=3D"pilcr=
ow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-6.4-4.3">complemented =
character classes ([^abc], [^a-z]);<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft=
/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4-4.3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-6.4-4.4">simple quanti=
fiers: "+" (one or more), "*" (zero or more), "?" (zero or
                        one), and their lazy versions ("+?", "*?", "??");<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4=
-4.4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-6.4-4.5">range quantif=
iers: "{x}" (exactly x occurrences), "{x,y}" (at least x, at
                        most y, occurrences), {x,} (x occurrences or more),=
 and their lazy
                        versions;<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2=
020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4-4.5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-6.4-4.6">the beginning=
-of-input ("^") and end-of-input ("$") anchors;<a href=3D"https://json-sche=
ma.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4-4.6" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-6.4-4.7">simple groupi=
ng ("(...)") and alternation ("|").<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft=
/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4-4.7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
        </ul>
<p id=3D"section-6.4-5">
                    Finally, implementations MUST NOT take regular expressi=
ons to be
                    anchored, neither at the beginning nor at the end. This=
 means, for instance,
                    the pattern "es" matches "expression".<a href=3D"https:=
//json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6.4-5" class=3D"pi=
lcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"extending">
<section id=3D"section-6.5">
        <h3 id=3D"name-extending-json-schema">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-6=
.5" class=3D"section-number selfRef">6.5. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-extending-json-schema" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">Extending JSON Schema</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-6.5-1">
                    Additional schema keywords and schema vocabularies MAY =
be defined
                    by any entity.  Save for explicit agreement, schema aut=
hors SHALL NOT
                    expect these additional keywords and vocabularies to be=
 supported by
                    implementations that do not explicitly document such su=
pport.
                    Implementations SHOULD treat keywords they do not suppo=
rt as annotations,
                    where the value of the keyword is the value of the anno=
tation.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-6.5-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-6.5-2">
                    Implementations MAY provide the ability to register or =
load handlers
                    for vocabularies that they do not support directly.  Th=
e exact mechanism
                    for registering and implementing such handlers is imple=
mentation-dependent.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-s=
chema-core#section-6.5-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-7">
      <h2 id=3D"name-keyword-behaviors">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keyword-behaviors" class=3D"section-n=
ame selfRef">Keyword Behaviors</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-7-1">
                JSON Schema keywords fall into several general behavior cat=
egories.
                Assertions validate that an instance satisfies constraints,=
 producing
                a boolean result.  Annotations attach information that appl=
ications
                may use in any way they see fit.
                Applicators apply subschemas to parts of the instance and c=
ombine
                their results.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#section-7-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7-2">
                Extension keywords SHOULD stay within these categories, kee=
ping in mind
                that annotations in particular are extremely flexible.  Com=
plex behavior
                is usually better delegated to applications on the basis of=
 annotation
                data than implemented directly as schema keywords.  However=
, extension
                keywords MAY define other behaviors for specialized purpose=
s.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-7-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7-3">
                Evaluating an instance against a schema involves processing=
 all of the
                keywords in the schema against the appropriate locations wi=
thin the instance.
                Typically, applicator keywords are processed until a schema=
 object with no
                applicators (and therefore no subschemas) is reached.  The =
appropriate
                location in the instance is evaluated against the assertion=
 and
                annotation keywords in the schema object, and their results=
 are gathered
                into the parent schema according to the rules of the applic=
ator.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-7-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7-4">
                Evaluation of a parent schema object can complete once all =
of its
                subschemas have been evaluated, although in some circumstan=
ces evaluation
                may be short-circuited due to assertion results.  When anno=
tations are
                being collected, some assertion result short-circuiting is =
not possible
                due to the need to examine all subschemas for annotation co=
llection, including
                those that cannot further change the assertion result.<a hr=
ef=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7-4" c=
lass=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div id=3D"scopes">
<section id=3D"section-7.1">
        <h3 id=3D"name-lexical-scope-and-dynamic-s">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-lexical-scope-and-dynamic-s" clas=
s=3D"section-name selfRef">Lexical Scope and Dynamic Scope</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-7.1-1">
                    While most JSON Schema keywords can be evaluated on the=
ir own,
                    or at most need to take into account the values or resu=
lts of
                    adjacent keywords in the same schema object, a few have=
 more
                    complex behavior.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dra=
ft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.1-2">
                    The lexical scope of a keyword is determined by the nes=
ted JSON
                    data structure of objects and arrays.  The largest such=
 scope
                    is an entire schema document.  The smallest scope is a =
single
                    schema object with no subschemas.<a href=3D"https://jso=
n-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.1-3">
                    Keywords MAY be defined with a partial value, such as a=
 URI-reference,
                    which must be resolved against another value, such as a=
nother
                    URI-reference or a full URI, which is found through the=
 lexical
                    structure of the JSON document.  The "$id", "$ref", and
                    "$dynamicRef" core keywords, and the "base" JSON Hyper-=
Schema
                    keyword, are examples of this sort of behavior.<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.1-3" c=
lass=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.1-4">
                    Note that some keywords, such as "$schema", apply to th=
e lexical
                    scope of the entire schema resource, and therefore MUST=
 only
                    appear in a schema resource's root schema.<a href=3D"ht=
tps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.1-4" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.1-5">
                    Other keywords may take into account the dynamic scope =
that
                    exists during the evaluation of a schema, typically tog=
ether
                    with an instance document.
                    The outermost dynamic scope is the schema object at
                    which processing begins, even if it is not a schema res=
ource root.
                    The path from this root schema to any particular keywor=
d (that
                    includes any "$ref" and "$dynamicRef" keywords that may=
 have
                    been resolved) is considered the keyword's "validation =
path."<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-7.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.1-6">
                    Lexical and dynamic scopes align until a reference keyw=
ord
                    is encountered.  While following the reference keyword =
moves processing
                    from one lexical scope into a different one, from the p=
erspective
                    of dynamic scope, following a reference is no different=
 from descending
                    into a subschema present as a value.  A keyword on the =
far side of
                    that reference that resolves information through the dy=
namic scope
                    will consider the originating side of the reference to =
be their
                    dynamic parent, rather than examining the local lexical=
ly enclosing parent.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-s=
chema-core#section-7.1-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.1-7">
                    The concept of dynamic scope is primarily used with "$d=
ynamicRef" and
                    "$dynamicAnchor", and should be considered an advanced =
feature
                    and used with caution when defining additional keywords=
.  It also appears
                    when reporting errors and collected annotations, as it =
may be possible
                    to revisit the same lexical scope repeatedly with diffe=
rent dynamic
                    scopes.  In such cases, it is important to inform the u=
ser of the
                    dynamic path that produced the error or annotation.<a h=
ref=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.1-7=
" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-7.2">
        <h3 id=3D"name-keyword-interactions">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keyword-interactions" class=3D"se=
ction-name selfRef">Keyword Interactions</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-7.2-1">
                    Keyword behavior MAY be defined in terms of the annotat=
ion results
                    of <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-=
12/json-schema-core#root" class=3D"xref">subschemas</a> (<a href=3D"https:/=
/json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#root" class=3D"xref">Sectio=
n 4.3.5</a>)</span> and/or adjacent keywords
                    (keywords within the same schema object) and their subs=
chemas.
                    Such keywords MUST NOT result in a circular dependency.
                    Keywords MAY modify their behavior based on the presenc=
e or absence
                    of another keyword in the same
                    <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/=
json-schema-core#schema-document" class=3D"xref">schema object</a> (<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#schema-document"=
 class=3D"xref">Section 4.3</a>)</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/=
draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a><=
/p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-7.3">
        <h3 id=3D"name-default-behaviors">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-default-behaviors" class=3D"secti=
on-name selfRef">Default Behaviors</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-7.3-1">
                    A missing keyword MUST NOT produce a false assertion re=
sult, MUST
                    NOT produce annotation results, and MUST NOT cause any =
other schema
                    to be evaluated as part of its own behavioral definitio=
n.
                    However, given that missing keywords do not contribute =
annotations,
                    the lack of annotation results may indirectly change th=
e behavior
                    of other keywords.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dr=
aft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p=
>
<p id=3D"section-7.3-2">
                    In some cases, the missing keyword assertion behavior o=
f a keyword is
                    identical to that produced by a certain value, and keyw=
ord definitions
                    SHOULD note such values where known.  However, even if =
the value which
                    produces the default behavior would produce annotation =
results if
                    present, the default behavior still MUST NOT result in =
annotations.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-7.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.3-3">
                    Because annotation collection can add significant cost =
in terms of both
                    computation and memory, implementations MAY opt out of =
this feature.
                    Keywords that are specified in terms of collected annot=
ations SHOULD
                    describe reasonable alternate approaches when appropria=
te.
                    This approach is demonstrated by the
                    "<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#items" class=3D"xref">items</a>" and
                    "<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#additionalProperties" class=3D"xref">additionalProperties</a>" =
keywords in this
                    document.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-=
12/json-schema-core#section-7.3-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.3-4">
                    Note that when no such alternate approach is possible f=
or a keyword,
                    implementations that do not support annotation collecti=
ons will not
                    be able to support those keywords or vocabularies that =
contain them.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-c=
ore#section-7.3-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-7.4">
        <h3 id=3D"name-identifiers">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.4. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-identifiers" class=3D"section-nam=
e selfRef">Identifiers</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-7.4-1">
                    Identifiers define URIs for a schema, or affect how suc=
h URIs are
                    resolved in <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dr=
aft/2020-12/json-schema-core#references" class=3D"xref">references</a> (<a =
href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#references" =
class=3D"xref">Section 8.2.3</a>)</span>, or both.
                    The Core vocabulary defined in this document defines se=
veral
                    identifying keywords, most notably "$id".<a href=3D"htt=
ps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.4-1" class=3D=
"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.4-2">
                    Canonical schema URIs MUST NOT change while processing =
an instance, but
                    keywords that affect URI-reference resolution MAY have =
behavior that
                    is only fully determined at runtime.<a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.4-2" class=3D"pilc=
row">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.4-3">
                    While custom identifier keywords are possible, vocabula=
ry designers should
                    take care not to disrupt the functioning of core keywor=
ds. For example,
                    the "$dynamicAnchor" keyword in this specification limi=
ts its URI resolution
                    effects to the matching "$dynamicRef" keyword, leaving =
the behavior
                    of "$ref" undisturbed.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.4-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a=
></p>
</section>
<div id=3D"applicators">
<section id=3D"section-7.5">
        <h3 id=3D"name-applicators">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.5" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.5. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-applicators" class=3D"section-nam=
e selfRef">Applicators</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-7.5-1">
                    Applicators allow for building more complex schemas tha=
n can be accomplished
                    with a single schema object.  Evaluation of an instance=
 against a
                    <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/=
json-schema-core#schema-document" class=3D"xref">schema document</a> (<a hr=
ef=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#schema-documen=
t" class=3D"xref">Section 4.3</a>)</span> begins by applying
                    the <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#root" class=3D"xref">root schema</a> (<a href=3D"https=
://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#root" class=3D"xref">Sect=
ion 4.3.5</a>)</span> to the complete instance
                    document.  From there, keywords known as applicators ar=
e used to determine
                    which additional schemas are applied.  Such schemas may=
 be applied in-place
                    to the current location, or to a child location.<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.5-1" c=
lass=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.5-2">
                    The schemas to be applied may be present as subschemas =
comprising all or
                    part of the keyword's value.  Alternatively, an applica=
tor may refer to
                    a schema elsewhere in the same schema document, or in a=
 different one.
                    The mechanism for identifying such referenced schemas i=
s defined by the
                    keyword.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#section-7.5-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.5-3">
                    Applicator keywords also define how subschema or refere=
nced schema
                    boolean <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/=
2020-12/json-schema-core#assertions" class=3D"xref">assertion</a> (<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#assertions" clas=
s=3D"xref">Section 7.6</a>)</span>
                    results are modified and/or combined to produce the boo=
lean result
                    of the applicator.  Applicators may apply any boolean l=
ogic operation
                    to the assertion results of subschemas, but MUST NOT in=
troduce new
                    assertion conditions of their own.<a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.5-3" class=3D"pilcro=
w">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.5-4">
                    <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/=
json-schema-core#annotations" class=3D"xref">Annotation</a> (<a href=3D"htt=
ps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#annotations" class=3D"x=
ref">Section 7.7</a>)</span> results are
                    preserved along with the instance location and the loca=
tion of
                    the schema keyword, so that applications can decide how=
 to
                    interpret multiple values.<a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.5-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<div id=3D"referenced">
<section id=3D"section-7.5.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-referenced-and-referencing-">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.5.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.5.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-referenced-and-referencing-" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Referenced and Referencing Schemas</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-7.5.1-1">
                        As noted in <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draf=
t/2020-12/json-schema-core#applicators" class=3D"xref">Section 7.5</a>, an =
applicator keyword may
                        refer to a schema to be applied, rather than includ=
ing it as a
                        subschema in the applicator's value.  In such situa=
tions, the
                        schema being applied is known as the referenced sch=
ema, while
                        the schema containing the applicator keyword is the=
 referencing schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-s=
chema-core#section-7.5.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.5.1-2">
                        While root schemas and subschemas are static concep=
ts based on a
                        schema's position within a schema document, referen=
ced and referencing
                        schemas are dynamic.  Different pairs of schemas ma=
y find themselves
                        in various referenced and referencing arrangements =
during the evaluation
                        of an instance against a schema.<a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.5.1-2" class=3D"pi=
lcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.5.1-3">
                        For some by-reference applicators, such as
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#ref" class=3D"xref">"$ref"</a> (<a href=3D"https://jso=
n-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#ref" class=3D"xref">Section 8.2=
.3.1</a>)</span>, the referenced schema can be determined
                        by static analysis of the schema document's lexical=
 scope.  Others,
                        such as "$dynamicRef" (with "$dynamicAnchor"), may =
make use of dynamic
                        scoping, and therefore only be resolvable in the pr=
ocess of evaluating
                        the schema with an instance.<a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.5.1-3" class=3D"pilcro=
w">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"assertions">
<section id=3D"section-7.6">
        <h3 id=3D"name-assertions">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.6" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.6. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-assertions" class=3D"section-name=
 selfRef">Assertions</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-7.6-1">
                    JSON Schema can be used to assert constraints on a JSON=
 document, which
                    either passes or fails the assertions.  This approach c=
an be used to validate
                    conformance with the constraints, or document what is n=
eeded to satisfy them.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#section-7.6-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.6-2">
                    JSON Schema implementations produce a single boolean re=
sult when evaluating
                    an instance against schema assertions.<a href=3D"https:=
//json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.6-2" class=3D"pi=
lcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.6-3">
                    An instance can only fail an assertion that is present =
in the schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-=
core#section-7.6-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-7.6.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-assertions-and-instance-pri">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.6.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.6.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-assertions-and-instance-pri" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Assertions and Instance Primitive Types</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-7.6.1-1">
                        Most assertions only constrain values within a cert=
ain
                        primitive type.  When the type of the instance is n=
ot of the type
                        targeted by the keyword, the instance is considered=
 to conform
                        to the assertion.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org=
/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.6.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</=
a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.6.1-2">
                        For example, the "maxLength" keyword from the compa=
nion
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#json-schema-validation" class=3D"xref">validation voca=
bulary</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#json-schema-validation" class=3D"xref">json-schema-validation</a>]</span=
>:
                        will only restrict certain strings
                        (that are too long) from being valid.  If the insta=
nce is a number,
                        boolean, null, array, or object, then it is valid a=
gainst this assertion.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#section-7.6.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.6.1-3">
                        This behavior allows keywords to be used more easil=
y with instances
                        that can be of multiple primitive types.  The compa=
nion validation
                        vocabulary also includes a "type" keyword which can=
 independently
                        restrict the instance to one or more primitive type=
s.  This allows
                        for a concise expression of use cases such as a fun=
ction that might
                        return either a string of a certain length or a nul=
l value:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
ection-7.6.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-7.6.1-4">
<pre>
{
    "type": ["string", "null"],
    "maxLength": 255
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-7.6.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-7.6.1-5" class=3D"keepWithPrevious">
                            If "maxLength" also restricted the instance typ=
e to be a string,
                            then this would be substantially more cumbersom=
e to express because
                            the example as written would not actually allow=
 null values.
                            Each keyword is evaluated separately unless exp=
licitly specified
                            otherwise, so if "maxLength" restricted the ins=
tance to strings,
                            then including "null" in "type" would not have =
any useful effect.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sch=
ema-core#section-7.6.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"annotations">
<section id=3D"section-7.7">
        <h3 id=3D"name-annotations">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.7" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.7. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-annotations" class=3D"section-nam=
e selfRef">Annotations</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-7.7-1">
                    JSON Schema can annotate an instance with information, =
whenever the instance
                    validates against the schema object containing the anno=
tation, and all of its
                    parent schema objects.  The information can be a simple=
 value, or can be
                    calculated based on the instance contents.<a href=3D"ht=
tps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7-1" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7-2">
                    Annotations are attached to specific locations in an in=
stance.
                    Since many subschemas can be applied to any single
                    location, applications may need to decide how to handle=
 differing
                    annotation values being attached to the same instance l=
ocation by
                    the same schema keyword in different schema objects.<a =
href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7-=
2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7-3">
                    Unlike assertion results, annotation data can take a wi=
de variety of forms,
                    which are provided to applications to use as they see f=
it.  JSON Schema
                    implementations are not expected to make use of the col=
lected information
                    on behalf of applications.<a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7-4">
                    Unless otherwise specified, the value of an annotation =
keyword
                    is the keyword's value.  However, other behaviors are p=
ossible.
                    For example, <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/d=
raft/2020-12/json-schema-core#json-hyper-schema" class=3D"xref">JSON Hyper-=
Schema's</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-=
core#json-hyper-schema" class=3D"xref">json-hyper-schema</a>]</span>
                    "links" keyword is a complex annotation that produces a=
 value based
                    in part on the instance data.<a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7-5">
                    While "short-circuit" evaluation is possible for assert=
ions, collecting
                    annotations requires examining all schemas that apply t=
o an instance
                    location, even if they cannot change the overall assert=
ion result.
                    The only exception is that subschemas of a schema objec=
t that has
                    failed validation MAY be skipped, as annotations are no=
t retained
                    for failing schemas.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/=
draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a><=
/p>
<section id=3D"section-7.7.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-collecting-annotations">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.7.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.7.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-collecting-annotations" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">Collecting Annotations</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1-1">
                        Annotations are collected by keywords that explicit=
ly define
                        annotation-collecting behavior.  Note that boolean =
schemas cannot
                        produce annotations as they do not make use of keyw=
ords.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-7.7.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1-2">
                        A collected annotation MUST include the following i=
nformation:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-cor=
e#section-7.7.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-7.7.1-3.1">
                                The name of the keyword that produces the a=
nnotation<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-7.7.1-3.1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-7.7.1-3.2">
                                The instance location to which it is attach=
ed, as a JSON Pointer<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#section-7.7.1-3.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-7.7.1-3.3">
                                The schema location path, indicating how re=
ference keywords
                                such as "$ref" were followed to reach the a=
bsolute schema location.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#section-7.7.1-3.3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-7.7.1-3.4">
                                The absolute schema location of the attachi=
ng keyword, as a URI.
                                This MAY be omitted if it is the same as th=
e schema location path
                                from above.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.o=
rg/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7.1-3.4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-7.7.1-3.5">
                                The attached value(s)<a href=3D"https://jso=
n-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7.1-3.5" class=3D"pil=
crow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          </ul>
<section id=3D"section-7.7.1.1">
            <h5 id=3D"name-distinguishing-among-multip">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.7.1.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.7.1.1. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-distinguishing-among-mult=
ip" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Distinguishing Among Multiple Values</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.1-1">
                            Applications MAY make decisions on which of mul=
tiple annotation values
                            to use based on the schema location that contri=
buted the value.
                            This is intended to allow flexible usage.  Coll=
ecting the schema location
                            facilitates such usage.<a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7.1.1-1" class=3D"pilcr=
ow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.1-2">
                            For example, consider this schema, which uses a=
nnotations and assertions from
                            the <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dr=
aft/2020-12/json-schema-core#json-schema-validation" class=3D"xref">Validat=
ion specification</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/jso=
n-schema-core#json-schema-validation" class=3D"xref">json-schema-validation=
</a>]</span>:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-c=
ore#section-7.7.1.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.1-3" class=3D"keepWithNext">
                                Note that some lines are wrapped for clarit=
y.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-7.7.1.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-7.7.1.1-4">
<pre>
{
    "title": "Feature list",
    "type": "array",
    "prefixItems": [
        {
            "title": "Feature A",
            "properties": {
                "enabled": {
                    "$ref": "#/$defs/enabledToggle",
                    "default": true
                }
            }
        },
        {
            "title": "Feature B",
            "properties": {
                "enabled": {
                    "description": "If set to null, Feature B
                                    inherits the enabled
                                    value from Feature A",
                    "$ref": "#/$defs/enabledToggle"
                }
            }
        }
    ],
    "$defs": {
        "enabledToggle": {
            "title": "Enabled",
            "description": "Whether the feature is enabled (true),
                            disabled (false), or under
                            automatic control (null)",
            "type": ["boolean", "null"],
            "default": null
        }
    }
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-7.7.1.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.1-5">
                            In this example, both Feature A and Feature B m=
ake use of the re-usable
                            "enabledToggle" schema.  That schema uses the "=
title", "description",
                            and "default" annotations.  Therefore the appli=
cation has to decide how
                            to handle the additional "default" value for Fe=
ature A, and the additional
                            "description" value for Feature B.<a href=3D"ht=
tps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7.1.1-5" cla=
ss=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.1-6">
                            The application programmer and the schema autho=
r need to agree on the
                            usage.  For this example, let's assume that the=
y agree that the most
                            specific "default" value will be used, and any =
additional, more generic
                            "default" values will be silently ignored.  Let=
's also assume that they
                            agree that all "description" text is to be used=
, starting with the most
                            generic, and ending with the most specific.  Th=
is requires the schema
                            author to write descriptions that work when com=
bined in this way.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sch=
ema-core#section-7.7.1.1-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.1-7">
                            The application can use the schema location pat=
h to determine which
                            values are which.  The values in the feature's =
immediate "enabled"
                            property schema are more specific, while the va=
lues under the re-usable
                            schema that is referenced to with "$ref" are mo=
re generic.  The schema
                            location path will show whether each value was =
found by crossing a
                            "$ref" or not.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7.1.1-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.1-8">
                            Feature A will therefore use a default value of=
 true, while Feature B
                            will use the generic default value of null.  Fe=
ature A will only
                            have the generic description from the "enabledT=
oggle" schema, while
                            Feature B will use that description, and also a=
ppend its locally
                            defined description that explains how to interp=
ret a null value.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sche=
ma-core#section-7.7.1.1-8" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.1-9">
                            Note that there are other reasonable approaches=
 that a different application
                            might take.  For example, an application may co=
nsider the presence of
                            two different values for "default" to be an err=
or, regardless of their
                            schema locations.<a href=3D"https://json-schema=
.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7.1.1-9" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-7.7.1.2">
            <h5 id=3D"name-annotations-and-assertions">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.7.1.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.7.1.2. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-annotations-and-assertion=
s" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Annotations and Assertions</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.2-1">
                            Schema objects that produce a false assertion r=
esult MUST NOT
                            produce any annotation results, whether from th=
eir own keywords
                            or from keywords in subschemas.<a href=3D"https=
://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7.1.2-1" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.2-2">
                            Note that the overall schema results may still =
include annotations
                            collected from other schema locations.  Given t=
his schema:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-cor=
e#section-7.7.1.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-7.7.1.2-3">
<pre>
{
    "oneOf": [
        {
            "title": "Integer Value",
            "type": "integer"
        },
        {
            "title": "String Value",
            "type": "string"
        }
    ]
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-7.7.1.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.2-4">
                            Against the instance <code>"This is a string"</=
code>, the
                            title annotation "Integer Value" is discarded b=
ecause the type assertion
                            in that schema object fails.  The title annotat=
ion "String Value"
                            is kept, as the instance passes the string type=
 assertions.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-7.7.1.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-7.7.1.3">
            <h5 id=3D"name-annotations-and-applicators">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.7.1.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.7.1.3. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-annotations-and-applicato=
rs" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Annotations and Applicators</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-7.7.1.3-1">
                            In addition to possibly defining annotation res=
ults of their own,
                            applicator keywords aggregate the annotations c=
ollected in their
                            subschema(s) or referenced schema(s).<a href=3D=
"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.7.1.3-1" =
class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-7.8">
        <h3 id=3D"name-reserved-locations">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.8" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.8. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-reserved-locations" class=3D"sect=
ion-name selfRef">Reserved Locations</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-7.8-1">
                    A fourth category of keywords simply reserve a location=
 to hold re-usable
                    components or data of interest to schema authors that i=
s not suitable
                    for re-use.  These keywords do not affect validation or=
 annotation results.
                    Their purpose in the core vocabulary is to ensure that =
locations are
                    available for certain purposes and will not be redefine=
d by extension
                    keywords.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-=
12/json-schema-core#section-7.8-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.8-2">
                    While these keywords do not directly affect results, as=
 explained in section
                    <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-s=
chema-core#non-schemas" class=3D"xref">9.4.2</a> unrecognized
                    extension keywords that reserve locations for re-usable=
 schemas may have
                    undesirable interactions with references in certain cir=
cumstances.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-cor=
e#section-7.8-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-7.9">
        <h3 id=3D"name-loading-instance-data">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7=
.9" class=3D"section-number selfRef">7.9. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-loading-instance-data" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">Loading Instance Data</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-7.9-1">
                    While none of the vocabularies defined as part of this =
or the associated documents
                    define a keyword which may target and/or load instance =
data, it is possible that
                    other vocabularies may wish to do so.<a href=3D"https:/=
/json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-7.9-1" class=3D"pil=
crow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.9-2">
                    Keywords MAY be defined to use JSON Pointers or Relativ=
e JSON Pointers to examine
                    parts of an instance outside the current evaluation loc=
ation.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-7.9-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-7.9-3">
                    Keywords that allow adjusting the location using a Rela=
tive JSON Pointer SHOULD
                    default to using the current location if a default is d=
esireable.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-7.9-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-8">
      <h2 id=3D"name-the-json-schema-core-vocabu">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-the-json-schema-core-vocabu" class=3D=
"section-name selfRef">The JSON Schema Core Vocabulary</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-8-1">
                Keywords declared in this section, which all begin with "$"=
, make up
                the JSON Schema Core vocabulary.  These keywords are either=
 required in
                order to process any schema or meta-schema, including those=
 split across
                multiple documents, or exist to reserve keywords for purpos=
es that
                require guaranteed interoperability.<a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8-2">
                The Core vocabulary MUST be considered mandatory at all tim=
es, in order
                to bootstrap the processing of further vocabularies.  Meta-=
schemas
                that use the <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft=
/2020-12/json-schema-core#vocabulary" class=3D"xref">"$vocabulary"</a> (<a =
href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#vocabulary" =
class=3D"xref">Section 8.1</a>)</span> keyword
                to declare the vocabularies in use MUST explicitly list the=
 Core vocabulary,
                which MUST have a value of true indicating that it is requi=
red.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-8-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8-3">
                The behavior of a false value for this vocabulary (and only=
 this
                vocabulary) is undefined, as is the behavior when "$vocabul=
ary"
                is present but the Core vocabulary is not included.  Howeve=
r, it
                is RECOMMENDED that implementations detect these cases and =
raise
                an error when they occur.  It is not meaningful to declare =
that
                a meta-schema optionally uses Core.<a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8-4">
                Meta-schemas that do not use "$vocabulary" MUST be consider=
ed to
                require the Core vocabulary as if its URI were present with=
 a value of true.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sche=
ma-core#section-8-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8-5">
                The current URI for the Core vocabulary is:
                &lt;https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/vocab/core&gt;.<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8-5=
" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8-6">
                The current URI for the corresponding meta-schema is:
                <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/meta=
/core">https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/meta/core</a></span>.<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8-6" cla=
ss=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8-7">
                While the "$" prefix is not formally reserved for the Core =
vocabulary,
                it is RECOMMENDED that extension keywords (in vocabularies =
or otherwise)
                begin with a character other than "$" to avoid possible fut=
ure collisions.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema=
-core#section-8-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div id=3D"vocabulary">
<section id=3D"section-8.1">
        <h3 id=3D"name-meta-schemas-and-vocabulari">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-meta-schemas-and-vocabulari" clas=
s=3D"section-name selfRef">Meta-Schemas and Vocabularies</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-8.1-1">
                    Two concepts, meta-schemas and vocabularies, are used t=
o inform an implementation
                    how to interpret a schema.  Every schema has a meta-sch=
ema, which can be declared
                    using the "$schema" keyword.<a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1-2">
                    The meta-schema serves two purposes:<a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1-2" class=3D"pilc=
row">=C2=B6</a></p>
<span class=3D"break"></span><dl class=3D"dlParallel" id=3D"section-8.1-3">
          <dt id=3D"section-8.1-3.1">Declaring the vocabularies in use</dt>
          <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-8.1-3.2">
                            The "$vocabulary" keyword, when it appears in a=
 meta-schema, declares
                            which vocabularies are available to be used in =
schemas that refer
                            to that meta-schema.  Vocabularies define keywo=
rd semantics,
                            as well as their general syntax.<a href=3D"http=
s://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1-3.2" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
          <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
<dt id=3D"section-8.1-3.3">Describing valid schema syntax</dt>
          <dd style=3D"margin-left: 1.5em" id=3D"section-8.1-3.4">
                            A schema MUST successfully validate against its=
 meta-schema, which
                            constrains the syntax of the available keywords=
.  The syntax described
                            is expected to be compatible with the vocabular=
ies declared; while
                            it is possible to describe an incompatible synt=
ax, such a meta-schema
                            would be unlikely to be useful.<a href=3D"https=
://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1-3.4" class=3D=
"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</dd>
        <dd class=3D"break"></dd>
</dl>
<p id=3D"section-8.1-4">
                    Meta-schemas are separate from vocabularies to allow fo=
r
                    vocabularies to be combined in different ways, and for =
meta-schema authors
                    to impose additional constraints such as forbidding cer=
tain keywords, or
                    performing unusually strict syntactical validation, as =
might be done
                    during a development and testing cycle.  Each vocabular=
y typically identifies
                    a meta-schema consisting only of the vocabulary's keywo=
rds.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-8.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1-5">
                    Meta-schema authoring is an advanced usage of JSON Sche=
ma, so the design of
                    meta-schema features emphasizes flexibility over simpli=
city.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-8.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div id=3D"keyword-schema">
<section id=3D"section-8.1.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-the-schema-keyword">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.1.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.1.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-the-schema-keyword" class=3D"=
section-name selfRef">The "$schema" Keyword</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.1-1">
                        The "$schema" keyword is both used as a JSON Schema=
 dialect identifier and
                        as the identifier of a resource which is itself a J=
SON Schema, which describes the
                        set of valid schemas written for this particular di=
alect.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-8.1.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.1-2">
                        The value of this keyword MUST be a <span><a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=
=3D"xref">URI</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span>
                        (containing a scheme) and this URI MUST be normaliz=
ed.
                        The current schema MUST be valid against the meta-s=
chema identified by this URI.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-=
12/json-schema-core#section-8.1.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.1-3">
                        If this URI identifies a retrievable resource, that=
 resource SHOULD be of
                        media type "application/schema+json".<a href=3D"htt=
ps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1.1-3" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.1-4">
                        The "$schema" keyword SHOULD be used in the documen=
t root schema object,
                        and MAY be used in the root schema objects of embed=
ded schema resources.
                        It MUST NOT appear in non-resource root schema obje=
cts.  If absent from
                        the document root schema, the resulting behavior is=
 implementation-defined.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#section-8.1.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.1-5">
                        Values for this property are defined elsewhere in t=
his and other documents,
                        and by other parties.<a href=3D"https://json-schema=
.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-8.1.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-the-vocabulary-keyword">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.1.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.1.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-the-vocabulary-keyword" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">The "$vocabulary" Keyword</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2-1">
                        The "$vocabulary" keyword is used in meta-schemas t=
o identify the
                        vocabularies available for use in schemas described=
 by that meta-schema.
                        It is also used to indicate whether each vocabulary=
 is required or optional,
                        in the sense that an implementation MUST understand=
 the required vocabularies
                        in order to successfully process the schema. Togeth=
er, this information forms
                        a dialect. Any vocabulary that is understood by the=
 implementation MUST be
                        processed in a manner consistent with the semantic =
definitions contained
                        within the vocabulary.<a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2-2">
                        The value of this keyword MUST be an object.  The p=
roperty names in the
                        object MUST be URIs (containing a scheme) and this =
URI MUST be normalized.
                        Each URI that appears as a property name identifies=
 a specific set of
                        keywords and their semantics.<a href=3D"https://jso=
n-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1.2-2" class=3D"pilcr=
ow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2-3">
                        The URI MAY be a URL, but the nature of the retriev=
able resource is
                        currently undefined, and reserved for future use.  =
Vocabulary authors
                        MAY use the URL of the vocabulary specification, in=
 a human-readable
                        media type such as text/html or text/plain, as the =
vocabulary URI.
                        <span class=3D"cref">
                            Vocabulary documents may be added in forthcomin=
g drafts.
                            For now, identifying the keyword set is deemed =
sufficient as that,
                            along with meta-schema validation, is how the c=
urrent "vocabularies"
                            work today.  Any future vocabulary document for=
mat will be specified
                            as a JSON document, so using text/html or other=
 non-JSON formats
                            in the meantime will not produce any future amb=
iguity.
            </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-8.1.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2-4">
                        The values of the object properties MUST be boolean=
s.
                        If the value is true, then implementations that do =
not recognize
                        the vocabulary MUST refuse to process any schemas t=
hat declare
                        this meta-schema with "$schema".  If the value is f=
alse, implementations
                        that do not recognize the vocabulary SHOULD proceed=
 with processing
                        such schemas.  The value has no impact if the imple=
mentation
                        understands the vocabulary.<a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2-5">
                        Per <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#extending" class=3D"xref">6.5</a>, unrecognized
                        keywords SHOULD be treated as annotations.
                        This remains the case for keywords defined
                        by unrecognized vocabularies.  It is not currently =
possible to distinguish
                        between unrecognized keywords that are defined in v=
ocabularies from
                        those that are not part of any vocabulary.<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1.2-5"=
 class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2-6">
                        The "$vocabulary" keyword SHOULD be used in the roo=
t schema of any schema
                        document intended for use as a meta-schema.  It MUS=
T NOT appear in subschemas.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12=
/json-schema-core#section-8.1.2-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2-7">
                        The "$vocabulary" keyword MUST be ignored in schema=
 documents that
                        are not being processed as a meta-schema.  This all=
ows validating
                        a meta-schema M against its own meta-schema M' with=
out requiring
                        the validator to understand the vocabularies declar=
ed by M.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
ection-8.1.2-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-8.1.2.1">
            <h5 id=3D"name-default-vocabularies">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.1.2.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.1.2.1. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-default-vocabularies" cla=
ss=3D"section-name selfRef">Default vocabularies</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2.1-1">
                            If "$vocabulary" is absent, an implementation M=
AY determine
                            behavior based on the meta-schema if it is reco=
gnized from the
                            URI value of the referring schema's "$schema" k=
eyword.
                            This is how behavior (such as Hyper-Schema usag=
e) has been
                            recognized prior to the existence of vocabulari=
es.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sectio=
n-8.1.2.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2.1-2">
                            If the meta-schema, as referenced by the schema=
, is not recognized,
                            or is missing, then the behavior is implementat=
ion-defined.
                            If the implementation
                            proceeds with processing the schema, it MUST as=
sume the use of the
                            core vocabulary.  If the implementation is buil=
t for a specific purpose,
                            then it SHOULD assume the use of all of the mos=
t relevant vocabularies
                            for that purpose.<a href=3D"https://json-schema=
.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1.2.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2.1-3">
                            For example, an implementation that is a valida=
tor
                            SHOULD assume the use of all vocabularies in th=
is
                            specification and the companion Validation spec=
ification.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-8.1.2.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-8.1.2.2">
            <h5 id=3D"name-non-inheritability-of-vocab">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.1.2.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.1.2.2. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-non-inheritability-of-voc=
ab" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Non-inheritability of vocabularies</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.2.2-1">
                            Note that the processing restrictions on "$voca=
bulary" mean that
                            meta-schemas that reference other meta-schemas =
using "$ref" or
                            similar keywords do not automatically inherit t=
he vocabulary
                            declarations of those other meta-schemas.  All =
such declarations
                            must be repeated in the root of each schema doc=
ument intended
                            for use as a meta-schema.  This is demonstrated=
 in
                            <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/=
2020-12/json-schema-core#example-meta-schema" class=3D"xref">the example me=
ta-schema</a> (<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema=
-core#example-meta-schema" class=3D"xref">Appendix D.2</a>)</span>.
                            <span class=3D"cref">
                                This requirement allows implementations to =
find all vocabulary
                                requirement information in a single place f=
or each meta-schema.
                                As schema extensibility means that there ar=
e endless potential
                                ways to combine more fine-grained meta-sche=
mas by reference,
                                requiring implementations to anticipate all=
 possibilities and
                                search for vocabularies in referenced meta-=
schemas would
                                be overly burdensome.
              </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#section-8.1.2.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-8.1.3">
          <h4 id=3D"name-updates-to-meta-schema-and-">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.1.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.1.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-updates-to-meta-schema-and-" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Updates to Meta-Schema and Vocabulary URIs</=
a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-8.1.3-1">
                        Updated vocabulary and meta-schema URIs MAY be publ=
ished between
                        specification drafts in order to correct errors.  I=
mplementations
                        SHOULD consider URIs dated after this specification=
 draft and
                        before the next to indicate the same syntax and sem=
antics
                        as those listed here.<a href=3D"https://json-schema=
.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.1.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-8.2">
        <h3 id=3D"name-base-uri-anchors-and-derefe">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-base-uri-anchors-and-derefe" clas=
s=3D"section-name selfRef">Base URI, Anchors, and Dereferencing</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-8.2-1">
                    To differentiate between schemas in a vast ecosystem, s=
chemas are
                    identified by <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/=
draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">URI</a> [<a href=3D"=
https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xr=
ef">RFC3986</a>]</span>, and can embed references
                    to other schemas by specifying their URI.<a href=3D"htt=
ps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2-1" class=3D=
"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2-2">
                    Several keywords can accept a relative <span><a href=3D=
"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"x=
ref">URI-reference</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span>,
                    or a value used to construct a relative URI-reference. =
 For these keywords,
                    it is necessary to establish a base URI in order to res=
olve the reference.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-8.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div id=3D"id-keyword">
<section id=3D"section-8.2.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-the-id-keyword">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.2.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.2.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-the-id-keyword" class=3D"sect=
ion-name selfRef">The "$id" Keyword</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.1-1">
                        The "$id" keyword identifies a schema resource with=
 its
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC6596" class=3D"xref">canonical</a> [<a href=3D"http=
s://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC6596" class=3D"xref">=
RFC6596</a>]</span> URI.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#section-8.2.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.1-2">
                        Note that this URI is an identifier and not necessa=
rily a network locator.
                        In the case of a network-addressable URL, a schema =
need not be downloadable
                        from its canonical URI.<a href=3D"https://json-sche=
ma.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.1-3">
                        If present, the value for this keyword MUST be a st=
ring, and MUST represent a
                        valid <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draf=
t/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">URI-reference</a> [<a hr=
ef=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=
=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span>.  This URI-reference
                        SHOULD be normalized, and MUST resolve to an
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">absolute-URI</a> [<a href=3D"h=
ttps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xre=
f">RFC3986</a>]</span> (without a fragment),
                        or to a URI with an empty fragment.<a href=3D"https=
://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.1-3" class=3D=
"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.1-4">
                        The empty fragment form is NOT RECOMMENDED and is r=
etained only
                        for backwards compatibility, and because the
                        application/schema+json media type defines that a U=
RI with an
                        empty fragment identifies the same resource as the =
same URI
                        with the fragment removed.  However, since this equ=
ivalence is not
                        part of the <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC 3986 normaliza=
tion process</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sch=
ema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span>,
                        implementers and schema authors cannot rely on gene=
ric URI libraries
                        understanding it.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org=
/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</=
a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.1-5">
                        Therefore, "$id" MUST NOT contain a non-empty fragm=
ent, and SHOULD NOT
                        contain an empty fragment.  The absolute-URI form M=
UST be considered
                        the canonical URI, regardless of the presence or ab=
sence of an empty fragment.
                        <span class=3D"cref">
                            An empty fragment is currently allowed because =
older meta-schemas have
                            an empty fragment in their $id (or previously, =
id).
                            A future draft may outright forbid even empty f=
ragments in "$id".
            </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-8.2.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.1-6">
                        The absolute-URI also serves as the base URI for re=
lative URI-references
                        in keywords within the schema resource, in accordan=
ce with
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC 3986 section 5.1.1</a> [<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" cl=
ass=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span> regarding base URIs
                        embedded in content.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.1-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.1-7">
                        The presence of "$id" in a subschema indicates that=
 the subschema constitutes
                        a distinct schema resource within a single schema d=
ocument.  Furthermore,
                        in accordance with <span><a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC 3986 se=
ction 5.1.2</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sche=
ma-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span>
                        regarding encapsulating entities, if an "$id" in a =
subschema is a relative
                        URI-reference, the base URI for resolving that refe=
rence is the URI of
                        the parent schema resource.<a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.1-7" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.1-8">
                        If no parent schema object explicitly identifies it=
self as a resource
                        with "$id", the base URI is that of the entire docu=
ment, as established
                        by the steps given in the <span><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#initial-base" class=3D"xref"=
>previous section.</a> (<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#initial-base" class=3D"xref">Section 9.1.1</a>)</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.1-8=
" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-8.2.1.1">
            <h5 id=3D"name-identifying-the-root-schema">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.2.1.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.2.1.1. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-identifying-the-root-sche=
ma" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Identifying the root schema</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.1.1-1">
                            The root schema of a JSON Schema document SHOUL=
D contain an "$id" keyword
                            with an <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">absolute-URI</a> [=
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" =
class=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span> (containing a scheme,
                            but no fragment).<a href=3D"https://json-schema=
.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.1.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"anchor">
<section id=3D"section-8.2.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-defining-location-independe">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.2.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.2.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-defining-location-independe" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Defining location-independent identifiers</a=
>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.2-1">
                        Using JSON Pointer fragments requires knowledge of =
the structure of the schema.
                        When writing schema documents with the intention to=
 provide re-usable
                        schemas, it may be preferable to use a plain name f=
ragment that is not tied to
                        any particular structural location.  This allows a =
subschema to be relocated
                        without requiring JSON Pointer references to be upd=
ated.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-8.2.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.2-2">
                        The "$anchor" and "$dynamicAnchor" keywords are use=
d to specify such
                        fragments.  They are identifier keywords that can o=
nly be used to create
                        plain name fragments, rather than absolute URIs as =
seen with "$id".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schem=
a-core#section-8.2.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.2-3">
                        The base URI to which the resulting fragment is app=
ended is the canonical
                        URI of the schema resource containing the "$anchor"=
 or "$dynamicAnchor"
                        in question.  As discussed in the previous section,=
 this is either the
                        nearest "$id" in the same or parent schema object, =
or the base URI
                        for the document as determined according to RFC 398=
6.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-8.2.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.2-4">
                        Separately from the usual usage of URIs, "$dynamicA=
nchor"
                        indicates that the fragment is an extension point w=
hen used with
                        the "$dynamicRef" keyword.  This low-level, advance=
d feature
                        makes it easier to extend recursive schemas such as=
 the meta-schemas,
                        without imposing any particular semantics on that e=
xtension.
                        See the section on <span><a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#dynamic-ref" class=3D"xref">"$dynam=
icRef"</a> (<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#dynamic-ref" class=3D"xref">Section 8.2.3.2</a>)</span>
                        for details.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draf=
t/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p=
>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.2-5">
                        In most cases, the normal fragment behavior both su=
ffices and
                        is more intuitive.  Therefore it is RECOMMENDED tha=
t "$anchor"
                        be used to create plain name fragments unless there=
 is a clear
                        need for "$dynamicAnchor".<a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.2-5" class=3D"pilcrow"=
>=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.2-6">
                        If present, the value of this keyword MUST be a str=
ing and MUST start with
                        a letter ([A-Za-z]) or underscore ("_"), followed b=
y any number of letters,
                        digits ([0-9]), hyphens ("-"), underscores ("_"), a=
nd periods (".").
                        This matches the US-ASCII part of XML's
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#xml-names" class=3D"xref">NCName production</a> [<a hr=
ef=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#xml-names" cla=
ss=3D"xref">xml-names</a>]</span>.
                        <span class=3D"cref">
                            Note that the anchor string does not include th=
e "#" character,
                            as it is not a URI-reference.  An "$anchor": "f=
oo" becomes the
                            fragment "#foo" when used in a URI.  See below =
for full examples.
            </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-8.2.2-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.2-7">
                        The effect of specifying the same fragment name mul=
tiple times within
                        the same resource, using any combination of "$ancho=
r" and/or
                        "$dynamicAnchor", is undefined.  Implementations MA=
Y
                        raise an error if such usage is detected.<a href=3D=
"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.2-7" cl=
ass=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"references">
<section id=3D"section-8.2.3">
          <h4 id=3D"name-schema-references">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.2.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.2.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-schema-references" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">Schema References</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3-1">
                        Several keywords can be used to reference a schema =
which is to be applied to the
                        current instance location. "$ref" and "$dynamicRef"=
 are applicator
                        keywords, applying the referenced schema to the ins=
tance.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-8.2.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3-2">
                        As the values of "$ref" and "$dynamicRef" are URI R=
eferences, this allows
                        the possibility to externalise or divide a schema a=
cross multiple files,
                        and provides the ability to validate recursive stru=
ctures through
                        self-reference.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/d=
raft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>=
</p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3-3">
                        The resolved URI produced by these keywords is not =
necessarily a network
                        locator, only an identifier. A schema need not be d=
ownloadable from the
                        address if it is a network-addressable URL, and imp=
lementations SHOULD NOT
                        assume they should perform a network operation when=
 they encounter
                        a network-addressable URI.<a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.3-3" class=3D"pilcrow"=
>=C2=B6</a></p>
<div id=3D"ref">
<section id=3D"section-8.2.3.1">
            <h5 id=3D"name-direct-references-with-ref">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.2.3.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.2.3.1. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-direct-references-with-re=
f" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Direct References with "$ref"</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3.1-1">
                            The "$ref" keyword is an applicator that is use=
d to reference a statically
                            identified schema.  Its results are the results=
 of the referenced schema.
                            <span class=3D"cref">
                                Note that this definition of how the result=
s are determined means that
                                other keywords can appear alongside of "$re=
f" in the same schema object.
              </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#section-8.2.3.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3.1-2">
                            The value of the "$ref" keyword MUST be a strin=
g which is a URI-Reference.
                            Resolved against the current URI base, it produ=
ces the URI of the schema
                            to apply.  This resolution is safe to perform o=
n schema load, as the
                            process of evaluating an instance cannot change=
 how the reference resolves.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#section-8.2.3.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"dynamic-ref">
<section id=3D"section-8.2.3.2">
            <h5 id=3D"name-dynamic-references-with-dyn">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.2.3.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.2.3.2. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-dynamic-references-with-d=
yn" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Dynamic References with "$dynamicRef"</a=
>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3.2-1">
                            The "$dynamicRef" keyword is an applicator that=
 allows for deferring the
                            full resolution until runtime, at which point i=
t is resolved each time it is
                            encountered while evaluating an instance.<a hre=
f=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.3.2=
-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3.2-2">
                            Together with "$dynamicAnchor", "$dynamicRef" i=
mplements a cooperative
                            extension mechanism that is primarily useful wi=
th recursive schemas
                            (schemas that reference themselves).  Both the =
extension point and the
                            runtime-determined extension target are defined=
 with "$dynamicAnchor",
                            and only exhibit runtime dynamic behavior when =
referenced with
                            "$dynamicRef".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.3.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3.2-3">
                            The value of the "$dynamicRef" property MUST be=
 a string which is
                            a URI-Reference.  Resolved against the current =
URI base, it produces
                            the URI used as the starting point for runtime =
resolution.  This initial
                            resolution is safe to perform on schema load.<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2=
.3.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3.2-4">
                            If the initially resolved starting point URI in=
cludes a fragment that
                            was created by the "$dynamicAnchor" keyword, th=
e initial URI MUST be
                            replaced by the URI (including the fragment) fo=
r the outermost schema
                            resource in the <span><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#scopes" class=3D"xref">dynamic sco=
pe</a> (<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
copes" class=3D"xref">Section 7.1</a>)</span> that defines
                            an identically named fragment with "$dynamicAnc=
hor".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-8.2.3.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3.2-5">
                            Otherwise, its behavior is identical to "$ref",=
 and no runtime
                            resolution is needed.<a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.3.2-5" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.3.2-6">
                            For a full example using these keyword, see app=
endix
                            <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#recursive-example" class=3D"xref">C</a>.
                            <span class=3D"cref">
                                The difference between the hyper-schema met=
a-schema in pre-2019
                                drafts and an this draft dramatically demon=
strates the utility
                                of these keywords.
              </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#section-8.2.3.2-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"defs">
<section id=3D"section-8.2.4">
          <h4 id=3D"name-schema-re-use-with-defs">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.2.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.2.4. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-schema-re-use-with-defs" clas=
s=3D"section-name selfRef">Schema Re-Use With "$defs"</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.4-1">
                        The "$defs" keyword reserves a location for schema
                        authors to inline re-usable JSON Schemas into a mor=
e general schema.
                        The keyword does not directly affect the validation=
 result.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
ection-8.2.4-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.4-2">
                        This keyword's value MUST be an object.
                        Each member value of this object MUST be a valid JS=
ON Schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-8.2.4-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.2.4-3">
                        As an example, here is a schema describing an array=
 of positive
                        integers, where the positive integer constraint is =
a subschema in
                        "$defs":<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/20=
20-12/json-schema-core#section-8.2.4-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-8.2.4-4">
<pre>
{
    "type": "array",
    "items": { "$ref": "#/$defs/positiveInteger" },
    "$defs": {
        "positiveInteger": {
            "type": "integer",
            "exclusiveMinimum": 0
        }
    }
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-8.2.4-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
</section>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-8.3">
        <h3 id=3D"name-comments-with-comment">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8=
.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">8.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-comments-with-comment" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">Comments With "$comment"</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-8.3-1">
                    This keyword reserves a location for comments from sche=
ma authors
                    to readers or maintainers of the schema.<a href=3D"http=
s://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.3-1" class=3D"=
pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.3-2">
                    The value of this keyword MUST be a string. Implementat=
ions MUST NOT present this
                    string to end users.  Tools for editing schemas SHOULD =
support displaying and
                    editing this keyword.  The value of this keyword MAY be=
 used in debug or error
                    output which is intended for developers making use of s=
chemas.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-8.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.3-3">
                    Schema vocabularies SHOULD allow "$comment" within any =
object containing
                    vocabulary keywords.  Implementations MAY assume "$comm=
ent" is allowed
                    unless the vocabulary specifically forbids it.  Vocabul=
aries MUST NOT
                    specify any effect of "$comment" beyond what is describ=
ed in this
                    specification.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/=
2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.3-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.3-4">
                    Tools that translate other media types or programming l=
anguages
                    to and from application/schema+json MAY choose to conve=
rt that media type or
                    programming language's native comments to or from "$com=
ment" values.
                    The behavior of such translation when both native comme=
nts and "$comment"
                    properties are present is implementation-dependent.<a h=
ref=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.3-4=
" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-8.3-5">
                    Implementations MAY strip "$comment" values at any poin=
t during processing.
                    In particular, this allows for shortening schemas when =
the size of deployed
                    schemas is a concern.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org=
/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.3-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>=
</p>
<p id=3D"section-8.3-6">
                    Implementations MUST NOT take any other action based on=
 the presence, absence,
                    or contents of "$comment" properties.  In particular, t=
he value of "$comment"
                    MUST NOT be collected as an annotation result.<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-8.3-6" c=
lass=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-9">
      <h2 id=3D"name-loading-and-processing-sche">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-loading-and-processing-sche" class=3D=
"section-name selfRef">Loading and Processing Schemas</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-9-1"></p>
<section id=3D"section-9.1">
        <h3 id=3D"name-loading-a-schema">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-loading-a-schema" class=3D"sectio=
n-name selfRef">Loading a Schema</a>
        </h3>
<div id=3D"initial-base">
<section id=3D"section-9.1.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-initial-base-uri">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.1.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.1.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-initial-base-uri" class=3D"se=
ction-name selfRef">Initial Base URI</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.1-1">
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC3986 Section 5.1</a> [<a hr=
ef=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=
=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span> defines how to determine the
                        default base URI of a document.<a href=3D"https://j=
son-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.1-1" class=3D"pil=
crow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.1-2">
                        Informatively, the initial base URI of a schema is =
the URI at which it was
                        found, whether that was a network location, a local=
 filesystem, or any other
                        situation identifiable by a URI of any known scheme=
.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-=
9.1.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.1-3">
                        If a schema document defines no explicit base URI w=
ith "$id"
                        (embedded in content), the base URI is that determi=
ned per
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC 3986 section 5</a> [<a hre=
f=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=
=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.1-4">
                        If no source is known, or no URI scheme is known fo=
r the source, a suitable
                        implementation-specific default URI MAY be used as =
described in
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC 3986 Section 5.1.4</a> [<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" cl=
ass=3D"xref">RFC3986</a>]</span>.  It is RECOMMENDED
                        that implementations document any default base URI =
that they assume.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sche=
ma-core#section-9.1.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.1-5">
                        If a schema object is embedded in a document of ano=
ther media type, then
                        the initial base URI is determined according to the=
 rules of that
                        media type.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft=
/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.1-6">
                        Unless the "$id" keyword described in an earlier se=
ction is present in the
                        root schema, this base URI SHOULD be considered the=
 canonical URI of the
                        schema document's root schema resource.<a href=3D"h=
ttps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.1-6" clas=
s=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-9.1.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-loading-a-referenced-schema">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.1.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.1.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-loading-a-referenced-schema" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Loading a referenced schema</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.2-1">
                        The use of URIs to identify remote schemas does not=
 necessarily mean anything is downloaded,
                        but instead JSON Schema implementations SHOULD unde=
rstand ahead of time which schemas they will be using,
                        and the URIs that identify them.<a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.2-1" class=3D"pi=
lcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.2-2">
                        When schemas are downloaded,
                        for example by a generic user-agent that does not k=
now until runtime which schemas to download,
                        see <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/=
2020-12/json-schema-core#hypermedia" class=3D"xref">Usage for Hypermedia</a=
> (<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#hyperm=
edia" class=3D"xref">Section 9.5.1</a>)</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-sche=
ma.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.2-3">
                        Implementations SHOULD be able to associate arbitra=
ry URIs with an arbitrary
                        schema and/or automatically associate a schema's "$=
id"-given URI, depending
                        on the trust that the validator has in the schema. =
 Such URIs and schemas
                        can be supplied to an implementation prior to proce=
ssing instances, or may
                        be noted within a schema document as it is processe=
d, producing associations
                        as shown in appendix <a href=3D"https://json-schema=
.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#idExamples" class=3D"xref">A</a>.<a hre=
f=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.2-3=
" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.2-4">
                        A schema MAY (and likely will) have multiple URIs, =
but there is no way for a
                        URI to identify more than one schema. When multiple=
 schemas try to identify
                        as the same URI, validators SHOULD raise an error c=
ondition.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-9.1.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-9.1.3">
          <h4 id=3D"name-detecting-a-meta-schema">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.1.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.1.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-detecting-a-meta-schema" clas=
s=3D"section-name selfRef">Detecting a Meta-Schema</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.3-1">
                        Implementations MUST recognize a schema as a meta-s=
chema if it
                        is being examined because it was identified as such=
 by another
                        schema's "$schema" keyword.  This means that a sing=
le schema
                        document might sometimes be considered a regular sc=
hema, and
                        other times be considered a meta-schema.<a href=3D"=
https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.3-1" cla=
ss=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.3-2">
                        In the case of examining a schema which is its own =
meta-schema,
                        when an implementation begins processing it as a re=
gular schema,
                        it is processed under those rules.  However, when l=
oaded a second
                        time as a result of checking its own "$schema" valu=
e, it is treated
                        as a meta-schema.  So the same document is processe=
d both ways in
                        the course of one session.<a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow"=
>=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.1.3-3">
                        Implementations MAY allow a schema to be explicitly=
 passed as a meta-schema,
                        for implementation-specific purposes, such as pre-l=
oading a commonly
                        used meta-schema and checking its vocabulary suppor=
t requirements
                        up front.  Meta-schema authors MUST NOT expect such=
 features to be
                        interoperable across implementations.<a href=3D"htt=
ps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.1.3-3" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-9.2">
        <h3 id=3D"name-dereferencing">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-dereferencing" class=3D"section-n=
ame selfRef">Dereferencing</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-9.2-1">
                    Schemas can be identified by any URI that has been give=
n to them, including
                    a JSON Pointer or their URI given directly by "$id".  I=
n all cases,
                    dereferencing a "$ref" reference involves first resolvi=
ng its value as a
                    URI reference against the current base URI per
                    <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/=
json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC 3986</a> [<a href=3D"https://j=
son-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC3986" class=3D"xref">RFC39=
86</a>]</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema=
-core#section-9.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2-2">
                    If the resulting URI identifies a schema within the cur=
rent document, or
                    within another schema document that has been made avail=
able to the implementation,
                    then that schema SHOULD be used automatically.<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.2-2" c=
lass=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2-3">
                    For example, consider this schema:<a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.2-3" class=3D"pilcro=
w">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-9.2-4">
<pre>
{
    "$id": "https://example.net/root.json",
    "items": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": { "$ref": "#item" }
    },
    "$defs": {
        "single": {
            "$anchor": "item",
            "type": "object",
            "additionalProperties": { "$ref": "other.json" }
        }
    }
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-9.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-9.2-5">
                    When an implementation encounters the &lt;#/$defs/singl=
e&gt; schema,
                    it resolves the "$anchor" value as a fragment name agai=
nst the current
                    base URI to form &lt;https://example.net/root.json#item=
&gt;.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-9.2-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2-6">
                    When an implementation then looks inside the &lt;#/item=
s&gt; schema, it
                    encounters the &lt;#item&gt; reference, and resolves th=
is to
                    &lt;https://example.net/root.json#item&gt;, which it ha=
s seen defined in
                    this same document and can therefore use automatically.=
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.2-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2-7">
                    When an implementation encounters the reference to "oth=
er.json", it resolves
                    this to &lt;https://example.net/other.json&gt;, which i=
s not defined in this
                    document.  If a schema with that identifier has otherwi=
se been supplied to
                    the implementation, it can also be used automatically.
                    <span class=3D"cref">
                        What should implementations do when the referenced =
schema is not known?
                        Are there circumstances in which automatic network =
dereferencing is
                        allowed?  A same origin policy?  A user-configurabl=
e option?  In the
                        case of an evolving API described by Hyper-Schema, =
it is expected that
                        new schemas will be added to the system dynamically=
, so placing an
                        absolute requirement of pre-loading schema document=
s is not feasible.
          </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sche=
ma-core#section-9.2-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div id=3D"embedded">
<section id=3D"section-9.2.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-json-pointer-fragments-and-">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.2.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.2.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-json-pointer-fragments-and-" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">JSON Pointer fragments and embedded schema r=
esources</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-1">
                        Since JSON Pointer URI fragments are constructed ba=
sed on the structure
                        of the schema document, an embedded schema resource=
 and its subschemas
                        can be identified by JSON Pointer fragments relativ=
e to either its own
                        canonical URI, or relative to any containing resour=
ce's URI.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-9.2.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-2">
                        Conceptually, a set of linked schema resources shou=
ld behave
                        identically whether each resource is a separate doc=
ument connected with
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#references" class=3D"xref">schema references</a> (<a h=
ref=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#references" c=
lass=3D"xref">Section 8.2.3</a>)</span>, or is structured as
                        a single document with one or more schema resources=
 embedded as
                        subschemas.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft=
/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.2.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-3">
                        Since URIs involving JSON Pointer fragments relativ=
e to the parent
                        schema resource's URI cease to be valid when the em=
bedded schema
                        is moved to a separate document and referenced, app=
lications and schemas
                        SHOULD NOT use such URIs to identify embedded schem=
a resources or
                        locations within them.<a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.2.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-4" class=3D"keepWithNext">
                            Consider the following schema document that con=
tains another
                            schema resource embedded within it:<a href=3D"h=
ttps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.2.1-4" clas=
s=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-9.2.1-5">
<pre>
{
    "$id": "https://example.com/foo",
    "items": {
        "$id": "https://example.com/bar",
        "additionalProperties": { }
    }
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-9.2.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-6">
                        The URI "https://example.com/foo#/items" points to =
the "items" schema,
                        which is an embedded resource.  The canonical URI o=
f that schema
                        resource, however, is "https://example.com/bar".<a =
href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.2.=
1-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-7">
                        For the "additionalProperties" schema within that e=
mbedded resource,
                        the URI "https://example.com/foo#/items/additionalP=
roperties" points
                        to the correct object, but that object's URI relati=
ve to its resource's
                        canonical URI is "https://example.com/bar#/addition=
alProperties".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-=
core#section-9.2.1-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-8" class=3D"keepWithNext">
                            Now consider the following two schema resources=
 linked by reference
                            using a URI value for "$ref":<a href=3D"https:/=
/json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.2.1-8" class=3D"p=
ilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-9.2.1-9">
<pre>
{
    "$id": "https://example.com/foo",
    "items": {
        "$ref": "bar"
    }
}

{
    "$id": "https://example.com/bar",
    "additionalProperties": { }
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-9.2.1-9" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-10" class=3D"keepWithPrevious">
                            Here we see that "https://example.com/bar#/addi=
tionalProperties",
                            using a JSON Pointer fragment appended to the c=
anonical URI of
                            the "bar" schema resource, is still valid, whil=
e
                            "https://example.com/foo#/items/additionalPrope=
rties", which relied
                            on a JSON Pointer fragment appended to the cano=
nical URI of the
                            "foo" schema resource, no longer resolves to an=
ything.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-9.2.1-10" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-11">
                        Note also that "https://example.com/foo#/items" is =
valid in both
                        arrangements, but resolves to a different value.  T=
his URI ends up
                        functioning similarly to a retrieval URI for a reso=
urce.  While this URI
                        is valid, it is more robust to use the "$id" of the=
 embedded or referenced
                        resource unless it is specifically desired to ident=
ify the object containing
                        the "$ref" in the second (non-embedded) arrangement=
.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-=
9.2.1-11" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-12">
                        An implementation MAY choose not to support address=
ing schema resource
                        contents by URIs using a base other than the resour=
ce's canonical URI,
                        plus a JSON Pointer fragment relative to that base.=
  Therefore, schema
                        authors SHOULD NOT rely on such URIs, as using them=
 may reduce interoperability.
                        <span class=3D"cref">
                            This is to avoid requiring implementations to k=
eep track of a whole
                            stack of possible base URIs and JSON Pointer fr=
agments for each,
                            given that all but one will be fragile if the s=
chema resources
                            are reorganized.  Some
                            have argued that this is easy so there is
                            no point in forbidding it, while others have ar=
gued that it complicates
                            schema identification and should be forbidden. =
 Feedback on this
                            topic is encouraged.
                            After some discussion, we feel that we need to =
remove the use of
                            "canonical" in favour of talking about JSON Poi=
nters which reference
                            across schema resource boundaries as undefined =
or even forbidden behavior
                            (https://github.com/json-schema-org/json-schema=
-spec/issues/937,
                            https://github.com/json-schema-org/json-schema-=
spec/issues/1183)
            </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-9.2.1-12" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.2.1-13">
                        Further examples of such non-canonical URI construc=
tion, as well as
                        the appropriate canonical URI-based fragments to us=
e instead,
                        are provided in appendix <a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#idExamples" class=3D"xref">A</a>.<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.2=
.1-13" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-9.3">
        <h3 id=3D"name-compound-documents">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-compound-documents" class=3D"sect=
ion-name selfRef">Compound Documents</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-9.3-1">
                    A Compound Schema Document is defined as a JSON documen=
t (sometimes called a "bundled" schema)
                    which has multiple embedded JSON Schema Resources bundl=
ed into the same document to
                    ease transportation.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/=
draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a><=
/p>
<p id=3D"section-9.3-2">
                    Each embedded Schema Resource MUST be treated as an ind=
ividual Schema Resource, following standard
                    schema loading and processing requirements, including d=
etermining vocabulary support.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#section-9.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-9.3.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-bundling">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.3.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.3.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-bundling" class=3D"section-na=
me selfRef">Bundling</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.1-1">
                        The bundling process for creating a Compound Schema=
 Document is defined as taking
                        references (such as "$ref") to an external Schema R=
esource and embedding the referenced
                        Schema Resources within the referring document. Bun=
dling SHOULD be done in such a way that
                        all URIs (used for referencing) in the base documen=
t and any referenced/embedded
                        documents do not require altering.<a href=3D"https:=
//json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.3.1-1" class=3D"=
pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.1-2">
                        Each embedded JSON Schema Resource MUST identify it=
self with a URI using the "$id" keyword,
                        and SHOULD make use of the "$schema" keyword to ide=
ntify the dialect it is using, in the root of the
                        schema resource. It is RECOMMENDED that the URI ide=
ntifier value of "$id" be an Absolute URI.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.3.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6<=
/a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.1-3">
                        When the Schema Resource referenced by a by-referen=
ce applicator is bundled, it is RECOMMENDED that
                        the Schema Resource be located as a value of a "$de=
fs" object at the containing schema's root.
                        The key of the "$defs" for the now embedded Schema =
Resource MAY be the "$id" of the bundled schema
                        or some other form of application defined unique id=
entifier (such as a UUID). This key is not
                        intended to be referenced in JSON Schema, but may b=
e used by an application to aid the
                        bundling process.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org=
/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.3.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</=
a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.1-4">
                        A Schema Resource MAY be embedded in a location oth=
er than "$defs" where the location is defined
                        as a schema value.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.or=
g/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.3.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6<=
/a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.1-5">
                        A Bundled Schema Resource MUST NOT be bundled by re=
placing the schema object from which it was
                        referenced, or by wrapping the Schema Resource in o=
ther applicator keywords.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/j=
son-schema-core#section-9.3.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.1-6">
                        In order to produce identical output, references in=
 the containing schema document to the
                        previously external Schema Resources MUST NOT be ch=
anged, and now resolve to a schema using the
                        "$id" of an embedded Schema Resource. Such identica=
l output includes validation evaluation and URIs
                        or paths used in resulting annotations or errors.<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.3=
.1-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.1-7">
                        While the bundling process will often be the main m=
ethod for creating a Compound Schema Document,
                        it is also possible and expected that some will be =
created by hand, potentially without individual
                        Schema Resources existing on their own previously.<=
a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.=
3.1-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-9.3.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-differing-and-default-diale">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.3.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.3.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-differing-and-default-diale" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Differing and Default Dialects</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.2-1">
                        When multiple schema resources are present in a sin=
gle document,
                        schema resources which do not define with which dia=
lect they should be processed
                        MUST be processed with the same dialect as the encl=
osing resource.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema=
-core#section-9.3.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.2-2">
                        Since any schema that can be referenced can also be=
 embedded, embedded schema resources MAY
                        specify different processing dialects using the "$s=
chema" values from their enclosing resource.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.3.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-9.3.3">
          <h4 id=3D"name-validating">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.3.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.3.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-validating" class=3D"section-=
name selfRef">Validating</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.3-1">
                        Given that a Compound Schema Document may have embe=
dded resources which identify as using different
                        dialects, these documents SHOULD NOT be validated b=
y applying a meta-schema
                        to the Compound Schema Document as an instance. It =
is RECOMMENDED that an alternate
                        validation process be provided in order to validate=
 Schema Documents. Each Schema Resource
                        SHOULD be separately validated against its associat=
ed meta-schema.
                        <span class=3D"cref">
                            If you know a schema is what's being validated,=
 you can identify if the schemas
                            is a Compound Schema Document or not, by way of=
 use of "$id", which identifies an
                            embedded resource when used not at the document=
's root.
            </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-9.3.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.3.3-2">
                        A Compound Schema Document in which all embedded re=
sources identify as using the same
                        dialect, or in which "$schema" is omitted and there=
fore defaults to that of the enclosing resource,
                        MAY be validated by applying the appropriate meta-s=
chema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-9.3.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-9.4">
        <h3 id=3D"name-caveats">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.4. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-caveats" class=3D"section-name se=
lfRef">Caveats</a>
        </h3>
<section id=3D"section-9.4.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-guarding-against-infinite-r">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.4.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.4.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-guarding-against-infinite-r" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Guarding Against Infinite Recursion</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.4.1-1">
                        A schema MUST NOT be run into an infinite loop agai=
nst an instance. For
                        example, if two schemas "#alice" and "#bob" both ha=
ve an "allOf" property
                        that refers to the other, a naive validator might g=
et stuck in an infinite
                        recursive loop trying to validate the instance.  Sc=
hemas SHOULD NOT make
                        use of infinite recursive nesting like this; the be=
havior is undefined.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-s=
chema-core#section-9.4.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<div id=3D"non-schemas">
<section id=3D"section-9.4.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-references-to-possible-non-">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.4.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.4.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-references-to-possible-non-" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">References to Possible Non-Schemas</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.4.2-1">
                        Subschema objects (or booleans) are recognized by t=
heir use with known
                        applicator keywords or with location-reserving keyw=
ords such as
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#defs" class=3D"xref">"$defs"</a> (<a href=3D"https://j=
son-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#defs" class=3D"xref">Section =
8.2.4</a>)</span> that take one or more subschemas
                        as a value.  These keywords may be "$defs" and the =
standard applicators
                        from this document, or extension keywords from a kn=
own vocabulary, or
                        implementation-specific custom keywords.<a href=3D"=
https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.4.2-1" cla=
ss=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.4.2-2">
                        Multi-level structures of unknown keywords are capa=
ble of introducing
                        nested subschemas, which would be subject to the pr=
ocessing rules for
                        "$id".  Therefore, having a reference target in suc=
h an unrecognized
                        structure cannot be reliably implemented, and the r=
esulting behavior
                        is undefined.  Similarly, a reference target under =
a known keyword,
                        for which the value is known not to be a schema, re=
sults in undefined
                        behavior in order to avoid burdening implementation=
s with the need
                        to detect such targets.
                        <span class=3D"cref">
                            These scenarios are analogous to fetching a sch=
ema over HTTP
                            but receiving a response with a Content-Type ot=
her than
                            application/schema+json.  An implementation can=
 certainly
                            try to interpret it as a schema, but the origin=
 server
                            offered no guarantee that it actually is any su=
ch thing.
                            Therefore, interpreting it as such has security=
 implications
                            and may produce unpredictable results.
            </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-9.4.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.4.2-3">
                        Note that single-level custom keywords with identic=
al syntax and
                        semantics to "$defs" do not allow for any interveni=
ng "$id" keywords,
                        and therefore will behave correctly under implement=
ations that attempt
                        to use any reference target as a schema.  However, =
this behavior is
                        implementation-specific and MUST NOT be relied upon=
 for interoperability.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#section-9.4.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-9.5">
        <h3 id=3D"name-associating-instances-and-s">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.5" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.5. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-associating-instances-and-s" clas=
s=3D"section-name selfRef">Associating Instances and Schemas</a>
        </h3>
<div id=3D"hypermedia">
<section id=3D"section-9.5.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-usage-for-hypermedia">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.5.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.5.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-usage-for-hypermedia" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">Usage for Hypermedia</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-9.5.1-1">
                        JSON has been adopted widely by HTTP servers for au=
tomated APIs and robots. This
                        section describes how to enhance processing of JSON=
 documents in a more RESTful
                        manner when used with protocols that support media =
types and
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#RFC8288" class=3D"xref">Web linking</a> [<a href=3D"ht=
tps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8288" class=3D"xref=
">RFC8288</a>]</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#section-9.5.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-9.5.1.1">
            <h5 id=3D"name-linking-to-a-schema">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.5.1.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.5.1.1. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-linking-to-a-schema" clas=
s=3D"section-name selfRef">Linking to a Schema</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-9.5.1.1-1">
                            It is RECOMMENDED that instances described by a=
 schema provide a link to
                            a downloadable JSON Schema using the link relat=
ion "describedby", as defined by
                            <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/=
2020-12/json-schema-core#W3C.REC-ldp-20150226" class=3D"xref">Linked Data P=
rotocol 1.0, section 8.1</a> [<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#W3C.REC-ldp-20150226" class=3D"xref">W3C.REC-ldp-20150=
226</a>]</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schem=
a-core#section-9.5.1.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.5.1.1-2">
                            In HTTP, such links can be attached to any resp=
onse using the
                            <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/=
2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8288" class=3D"xref">Link header</a> [<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8288" class=
=3D"xref">RFC8288</a>]</span>. An example of such a header would be:<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.5.1.1-=
2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-9.5.1.1-3">
<pre>
        Link: &lt;https://example.com/my-hyper-schema&gt;; rel=3D"described=
by"

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-9.5.1.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-9.5.1.2">
            <h5 id=3D"name-usage-over-http">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-9=
.5.1.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">9.5.1.2. </a><a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-usage-over-http" class=3D=
"section-name selfRef">Usage Over HTTP</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-9.5.1.2-1">
                            When used for hypermedia systems over a network=
,
                            <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/=
2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC7231" class=3D"xref">HTTP</a> [<a href=3D"https=
://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC7231" class=3D"xref">R=
FC7231</a>]</span> is frequently the protocol of choice for
                            distributing schemas. Misbehaving clients can p=
ose problems for server
                            maintainers if they pull a schema over the netw=
ork more frequently than
                            necessary, when it's instead possible to cache =
a schema for a long period of
                            time.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2=
020-12/json-schema-core#section-9.5.1.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.5.1.2-2">
                            HTTP servers SHOULD set long-lived caching head=
ers on JSON Schemas.
                            HTTP clients SHOULD observe caching headers and=
 not re-request documents within
                            their freshness period.
                            Distributed systems SHOULD make use of a shared=
 cache and/or caching proxy.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#section-9.5.1.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-9.5.1.2-3">
                            Clients SHOULD set or prepend a User-Agent head=
er specific to the JSON Schema
                            implementation or software product. Since symbo=
ls are listed in decreasing order
                            of significance, the JSON Schema library name/v=
ersion should precede the more
                            generic HTTP library name (if any). For example=
:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-=
9.5.1.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-9.5.1.2-4">
<pre>
        User-Agent: product-name/5.4.1 so-cool-json-schema/1.0.2 curl/7.43.=
0

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-9.5.1.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-9.5.1.2-5">
                            Clients SHOULD be able to make requests with a =
"From" header so that server
                            operators can contact the owner of a potentiall=
y misbehaving script.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#section-9.5.1.2-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
</div>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-10">
      <h2 id=3D"name-a-vocabulary-for-applying-s">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-a-vocabulary-for-applying-s" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">A Vocabulary for Applying Subschemas</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-10-1">
                This section defines a vocabulary of applicator keywords th=
at
                are RECOMMENDED for use as the basis of other vocabularies.=
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10-2">
                Meta-schemas that do not use "$vocabulary" SHOULD be consid=
ered to
                require this vocabulary as if its URI were present with a v=
alue of true.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-c=
ore#section-10-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10-3">
                The current URI for this vocabulary, known as the Applicato=
r vocabulary, is:
                &lt;https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/vocab/applicator&=
gt;.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-10-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10-4">
                The current URI for the corresponding meta-schema is:
                <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/meta=
/applicator">https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/meta/applicator</a></spa=
n>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sectio=
n-10-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-10.1">
        <h3 id=3D"name-keyword-independence">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keyword-independence" class=3D"=
section-name selfRef">Keyword Independence</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-10.1-1">
                    Schema keywords typically operate independently, withou=
t
                    affecting each other's outcomes.<a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.1-2">
                    For schema author convenience, there are some exception=
s among the
                    keywords in this vocabulary:<a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-10.1-3.1">
                            "additionalProperties", whose behavior is defin=
ed in terms of
                            "properties" and "patternProperties"<a href=3D"=
https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.1-3.1" cl=
ass=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-10.1-3.2">
                            "items", whose behavior is defined in terms of =
"prefixItems"<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-c=
ore#section-10.1-3.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-10.1-3.3">
                            "contains", whose behavior is affected by the p=
resence and value of
                            "minContains", in the Validation vocabulary<a h=
ref=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.1-=
3.3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
        </ul>
</section>
<div id=3D"in-place">
<section id=3D"section-10.2">
        <h3 id=3D"name-keywords-for-applying-subsc">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keywords-for-applying-subsc" cl=
ass=3D"section-name selfRef">Keywords for Applying Subschemas in Place</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-10.2-1">
                    These keywords apply subschemas to the same location in=
 the instance
                    as the parent schema is being applied.  They allow comb=
ining
                    or modifying the subschema results in various ways.<a h=
ref=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.2-=
1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2-2">
                    Subschemas of these keywords evaluate the instance comp=
letely independently
                    such that the results of one such subschema MUST NOT im=
pact the results of sibling
                    subschemas.  Therefore subschemas may be applied in
                    any order.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/json-schema-core#section-10.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div id=3D"logic">
<section id=3D"section-10.2.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-keywords-for-applying-subsch">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keywords-for-applying-subsc=
h" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Keywords for Applying Subschemas With Log=
ic</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.1-1">
                        These keywords correspond to logical operators for =
combining or modifying
                        the boolean assertion results of the subschemas.  T=
hey have no direct
                        impact on annotation collection, although they enab=
le the same annotation
                        keyword to be applied to an instance location with =
different values.
                        Annotation keywords define their own rules for comb=
ining such values.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sch=
ema-core#section-10.2.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div id=3D"allOf">
<section id=3D"section-10.2.1.1">
            <h5 id=3D"name-allof">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.1.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.1.1. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-allof" class=3D"section=
-name selfRef">allOf</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.1.1-1">
                            This keyword's value MUST be a non-empty array.
                            Each item of the array MUST be a valid JSON Sch=
ema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-10.2.1.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.1.1-2">
                            An instance validates successfully against this=
 keyword if it validates
                            successfully against all schemas defined by thi=
s keyword's value.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sch=
ema-core#section-10.2.1.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-10.2.1.2">
            <h5 id=3D"name-anyof">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.1.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.1.2. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-anyof" class=3D"section=
-name selfRef">anyOf</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.1.2-1">
                            This keyword's value MUST be a non-empty array.
                            Each item of the array MUST be a valid JSON Sch=
ema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-10.2.1.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.1.2-2">
                            An instance validates successfully against this=
 keyword if it validates
                            successfully against at least one schema define=
d by this keyword's value.
                            Note that when annotations are being collected,=
 all subschemas MUST
                            be examined so that annotations are collected f=
rom each subschema
                            that validates successfully.<a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.2.1.2-2" class=3D=
"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-10.2.1.3">
            <h5 id=3D"name-oneof">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.1.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.1.3. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-oneof" class=3D"section=
-name selfRef">oneOf</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.1.3-1">
                            This keyword's value MUST be a non-empty array.
                            Each item of the array MUST be a valid JSON Sch=
ema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-10.2.1.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.1.3-2">
                            An instance validates successfully against this=
 keyword if it validates
                            successfully against exactly one schema defined=
 by this keyword's value.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/j=
son-schema-core#section-10.2.1.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<div id=3D"not">
<section id=3D"section-10.2.1.4">
            <h5 id=3D"name-not">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.1.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.1.4. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-not" class=3D"section-n=
ame selfRef">not</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.1.4-1">
                            This keyword's value MUST be a valid JSON Schem=
a.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-10.2.1.4-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.1.4-2">
                            An instance is valid against this keyword if it=
 fails to validate
                            successfully against the schema defined by this=
 keyword.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-10.2.1.4-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"conditional">
<section id=3D"section-10.2.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-keywords-for-applying-subsche">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keywords-for-applying-subsc=
he" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Keywords for Applying Subschemas Conditi=
onally</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2-1">
                        Three of these keywords work together to implement =
conditional
                        application of a subschema based on the outcome of =
another subschema.
                        The fourth is a shortcut for a specific conditional=
 case.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-10.2.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2-2">
                        "if", "then", and "else" MUST NOT interact with eac=
h other across
                        subschema boundaries.  In other words, an "if" in o=
ne
                        branch of an "allOf" MUST NOT have an impact on a "=
then"
                        or "else" in another branch.<a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.2.2-2" class=3D"pilcr=
ow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2-3">
                        There is no default behavior for "if", "then", or "=
else"
                        when they are not present.  In particular, they MUS=
T NOT
                        be treated as if present with an empty schema, and =
when
                        "if" is not present, both "then" and "else" MUST be
                        entirely ignored.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org=
/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.2.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6<=
/a></p>
<section id=3D"section-10.2.2.1">
            <h5 id=3D"name-if">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.2.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.2.1. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-if" class=3D"section-na=
me selfRef">if</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.1-1">
                            This keyword's value MUST be a valid JSON Schem=
a.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-10.2.2.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.1-2">
                            This validation outcome of this keyword's subsc=
hema
                            has no direct effect on the overall validation
                            result.  Rather, it controls which of the "then=
"
                            or "else" keywords are evaluated.<a href=3D"htt=
ps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.2.2.1-2" cla=
ss=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.1-3">
                            Instances that successfully validate against th=
is
                            keyword's subschema MUST also be valid against
                            the subschema value of the "then" keyword, if
                            present.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draf=
t/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.2.2.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>=
</p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.1-4">
                            Instances that fail to validate against this
                            keyword's subschema MUST also be valid against
                            the subschema value of the "else" keyword, if
                            present.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draf=
t/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.2.2.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>=
</p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.1-5">
                            If <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dra=
ft/2020-12/json-schema-core#annotations" class=3D"xref">annotations</a> (<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#annotations=
" class=3D"xref">Section 7.7</a>)</span>
                            are being collected, they are collected from th=
is
                            keyword's subschema in the usual way, including=
 when
                            the keyword is present without either "then" or=
 "else".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
ection-10.2.2.1-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-10.2.2.2">
            <h5 id=3D"name-then">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.2.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.2.2. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-then" class=3D"section-=
name selfRef">then</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.2-1">
                            This keyword's value MUST be a valid JSON Schem=
a.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-10.2.2.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.2-2">
                            When "if" is present, and the instance successf=
ully
                            validates against its subschema, then validatio=
n
                            succeeds against this keyword if the instance a=
lso
                            successfully validates against this keyword's s=
ubschema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-10.2.2.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.2-3">
                            This keyword has no effect when "if" is absent,=
 or
                            when the instance fails to validate against its
                            subschema.  Implementations MUST NOT evaluate
                            the instance against this keyword, for either v=
alidation
                            or annotation collection purposes, in such case=
s.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-10.2.2.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-10.2.2.3">
            <h5 id=3D"name-else">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.2.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.2.3. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-else" class=3D"section-=
name selfRef">else</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.3-1">
                            This keyword's value MUST be a valid JSON Schem=
a.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-10.2.2.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.3-2">
                            When "if" is present, and the instance fails to
                            validate against its subschema, then validation
                            succeeds against this keyword if the instance
                            successfully validates against this keyword's s=
ubschema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#=
section-10.2.2.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.3-3">
                            This keyword has no effect when "if" is absent,=
 or
                            when the instance successfully validates agains=
t its
                            subschema.  Implementations MUST NOT evaluate
                            the instance against this keyword, for either v=
alidation
                            or annotation collection purposes, in such case=
s.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-10.2.2.3-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-10.2.2.4">
            <h5 id=3D"name-dependentschemas">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.2.2.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.2.2.4. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-dependentschemas" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">dependentSchemas</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.4-1">
                            This keyword specifies subschemas that are eval=
uated if the instance
                            is an object and contains a certain property.<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.=
2.2.4-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.4-2">
                            This keyword's value MUST be an object.
                            Each value in the object MUST be a valid JSON S=
chema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-10.2.2.4-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.4-3">
                            If the object key is a property in the instance=
, the entire
                            instance must validate against the subschema.  =
Its use is
                            dependent on the presence of the property.<a hr=
ef=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.2.2=
.4-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.2.2.4-4">
                            Omitting this keyword has the same behavior as =
an empty object.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schem=
a-core#section-10.2.2.4-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
</div>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-10.3">
        <h3 id=3D"name-keywords-for-applying-subschem">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keywords-for-applying-subschem"=
 class=3D"section-name selfRef">Keywords for Applying Subschemas to Child I=
nstances</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-10.3-1">
                    Each of these keywords defines a rule for applying its
                    subschema(s) to child instances, specifically object
                    properties and array items, and combining their results=
.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-=
10.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-10.3.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-keywords-for-applying-subschema">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keywords-for-applying-subsc=
hema" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Keywords for Applying Subschemas to Ar=
rays</a>
          </h4>
<section id=3D"section-10.3.1.1">
            <h5 id=3D"name-prefixitems">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3.1.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3.1.1. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-prefixitems" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">prefixItems</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.1-1">
                            The value of "prefixItems" MUST be a non-empty =
array of valid JSON Schemas.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#section-10.3.1.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.1-2">
                            Validation succeeds if each element of the inst=
ance validates
                            against the schema at the same position, if any=
.  This keyword
                            does not constrain the length of the array.  If=
 the array is longer
                            than this keyword's value, this keyword validat=
es only the
                            prefix of matching length.<a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.1.1-2" class=3D"p=
ilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.1-3">
                            This keyword produces an annotation value which=
 is the largest
                            index to which this keyword applied a subschema=
.  The value
                            MAY be a boolean true if a subschema was applie=
d to every
                            index of the instance, such as is produced by t=
he "items" keyword.
                            This annotation affects the behavior of "items"=
 and "unevaluatedItems".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#section-10.3.1.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.1-4">
                            Omitting this keyword has the same assertion be=
havior as
                            an empty array.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.o=
rg/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.1.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
</section>
<div id=3D"items">
<section id=3D"section-10.3.1.2">
            <h5 id=3D"name-items">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3.1.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3.1.2. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-items" class=3D"section=
-name selfRef">items</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.2-1">
                            The value of "items" MUST be a valid JSON Schem=
a.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-10.3.1.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.2-2">
                            This keyword applies its subschema to all insta=
nce elements
                            at indexes greater than the length of the "pref=
ixItems" array
                            in the same schema object, as reported by the a=
nnotation result
                            of that "prefixItems" keyword.  If no such anno=
tation
                            result exists, "items" applies its subschema to=
 all instance
                            array elements.
                            <span class=3D"cref">
                                Note that the behavior of "items" without "=
prefixItems" is
                                identical to that of the schema form of "it=
ems" in prior drafts.
                                When "prefixItems" is present, the behavior=
 of "items" is
                                identical to the former "additionalItems" k=
eyword.
              </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#section-10.3.1.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.2-3">
                            If the "items" subschema is applied to any
                            positions within the instance array, it produce=
s an
                            annotation result of boolean true, indicating t=
hat all remaining array
                            elements have been evaluated against this keywo=
rd's subschema.
                            This annotation affects the behavior of "uneval=
uatedItems" in the
                            Unevaluated vocabulary.<a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.1.2-3" class=3D"pilc=
row">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.2-4">
                            Omitting this keyword has the same assertion be=
havior as
                            an empty schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.1.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.2-5">
                            Implementations MAY choose to implement or opti=
mize this keyword
                            in another way that produces the same effect, s=
uch as by directly
                            checking for the presence and size of a "prefix=
Items" array.
                            Implementations that do not support annotation =
collection MUST do so.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#section-10.3.1.2-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-10.3.1.3">
            <h5 id=3D"name-contains">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3.1.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3.1.3. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-contains" class=3D"sect=
ion-name selfRef">contains</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.3-1">
                            The value of this keyword MUST be a valid JSON =
Schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-10.3.1.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.3-2">
                            An array instance is valid against "contains" i=
f at least one of
                            its elements is valid against the given schema,
                            except when "minContains" is present and has a =
value of 0, in which
                            case an array instance MUST be considered valid=
 against the "contains" keyword,
                            even if none of its elements is valid against t=
he given schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schem=
a-core#section-10.3.1.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.3-3">
                            This keyword produces an annotation value which=
 is an array of
                            the indexes to which this keyword validates suc=
cessfully when applying
                            its subschema, in ascending order. The value MA=
Y be a boolean "true" if
                            the subschema validates successfully when appli=
ed to every index of the
                            instance. The annotation MUST be present if the=
 instance array to which
                            this keyword's schema applies is empty.<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.1.3=
-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.3-4">
                            This annotation affects the behavior of "uneval=
uatedItems" in the
                            Unevaluated vocabulary, and MAY also be used to=
 implement the
                            "minContains" and "maxContains" keywords in the=
 Validation vocabulary.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/jso=
n-schema-core#section-10.3.1.3-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.1.3-5">
                            The subschema MUST be applied to every array el=
ement even after the first
                            match has been found, in order to collect annot=
ations for use by other
                            keywords. This is to ensure that all possible a=
nnotations are collected.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/j=
son-schema-core#section-10.3.1.3-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-10.3.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-keywords-for-applying-subschemas">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keywords-for-applying-subsc=
hemas" class=3D"section-name selfRef">Keywords for Applying Subschemas to O=
bjects</a>
          </h4>
<section id=3D"section-10.3.2.1">
            <h5 id=3D"name-properties">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3.2.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3.2.1. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-properties" class=3D"se=
ction-name selfRef">properties</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.1-1">
                            The value of "properties" MUST be an object.
                            Each value of this object MUST be a valid JSON =
Schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-10.3.2.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.1-2">
                            Validation succeeds if, for each name that appe=
ars in both
                            the instance and as a name within this keyword'=
s value, the child
                            instance for that name successfully validates a=
gainst the
                            corresponding schema.<a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.2.1-2" class=3D"pilcro=
w">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.1-3">
                            The annotation result of this keyword is the se=
t of instance
                            property names matched by this keyword.
                            This annotation affects the behavior of "additi=
onalProperties" (in
                            this vocabulary) and "unevaluatedProperties" in=
 the Unevaluated vocabulary.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#section-10.3.2.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.1-4">
                            Omitting this keyword has the same assertion be=
havior as
                            an empty object.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.2.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-10.3.2.2">
            <h5 id=3D"name-patternproperties">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3.2.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3.2.2. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-patternproperties" clas=
s=3D"section-name selfRef">patternProperties</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.2-1">
                            The value of "patternProperties" MUST be an obj=
ect. Each property name
                            of this object SHOULD be a valid regular expres=
sion, according to the
                            ECMA-262 regular expression dialect. Each prope=
rty value of this object
                            MUST be a valid JSON Schema.<a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.2.2-1" class=3D=
"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.2-2">
                            Validation succeeds if, for each instance name =
that matches any
                            regular expressions that appear as a property n=
ame in this keyword's value,
                            the child instance for that name successfully v=
alidates against each
                            schema that corresponds to a matching regular e=
xpression.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-10.3.2.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.2-3">
                            The annotation result of this keyword is the se=
t of instance
                            property names matched by this keyword.
                            This annotation affects the behavior of "additi=
onalProperties" (in this
                            vocabulary) and "unevaluatedProperties" (in the=
 Unevaluated vocabulary).<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/j=
son-schema-core#section-10.3.2.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.2-4">
                            Omitting this keyword has the same assertion be=
havior as
                            an empty object.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.2.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<div id=3D"additionalProperties">
<section id=3D"section-10.3.2.3">
            <h5 id=3D"name-additionalproperties">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3.2.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3.2.3. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-additionalproperties" c=
lass=3D"section-name selfRef">additionalProperties</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.3-1">
                            The value of "additionalProperties" MUST be a v=
alid JSON Schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sche=
ma-core#section-10.3.2.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.3-2">
                            The behavior of this keyword depends on the pre=
sence and
                            annotation results of "properties" and "pattern=
Properties"
                            within the same schema object.
                            Validation with "additionalProperties" applies =
only to the child
                            values of instance names that do not appear in =
the annotation
                            results of either "properties" or "patternPrope=
rties".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-10.3.2.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.3-3">
                            For all such properties, validation succeeds if=
 the child instance
                            validates against the "additionalProperties" sc=
hema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-10.3.2.3-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.3-4">
                            The annotation result of this keyword is the se=
t of instance
                            property names validated by this keyword's subs=
chema.
                            This annotation affects the behavior of "uneval=
uatedProperties"
                            in the Unevaluated vocabulary.<a href=3D"https:=
//json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.2.3-4" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.3-5">
                            Omitting this keyword has the same assertion be=
havior as
                            an empty schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-10.3.2.3-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.3-6">
                            Implementations MAY choose to implement or opti=
mize this keyword
                            in another way that produces the same effect, s=
uch as by directly
                            checking the names in "properties" and the patt=
erns in
                            "patternProperties" against the instance proper=
ty set.
                            Implementations that do not support annotation =
collection MUST do so.
                            <span class=3D"cref">
                                In defining this option, it seems there is =
the potential for
                                ambiguity in the output format. The ambigui=
ty does not affect validation results,
                                but it does affect the resulting output for=
mat.
                                The ambiguity allows for multiple valid out=
put results depending on whether annotations
                                are used or a solution that "produces the s=
ame effect" as draft-07. It is understood
                                that annotations from failing schemas are d=
ropped.
                                See our
                                [Decision Record](https://github.com/json-s=
chema-org/json-schema-spec/tree/HEAD/adr/2022-04-08-cref-for-ambiguity-and-=
fix-later-gh-spec-issue-1172.md)
                                for further details.
              </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#section-10.3.2.3-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-10.3.2.4">
            <h5 id=3D"name-propertynames">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
0.3.2.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">10.3.2.4. </a><a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-propertynames" class=3D=
"section-name selfRef">propertyNames</a>
            </h5>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.4-1">
                            The value of "propertyNames" MUST be a valid JS=
ON Schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-10.3.2.4-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.4-2">
                            If the instance is an object, this keyword vali=
dates if every property name in
                            the instance validates against the provided sch=
ema.
                            Note the property name that the schema is testi=
ng will always be a string.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12=
/json-schema-core#section-10.3.2.4-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-10.3.2.4-3">
                            Omitting this keyword has the same behavior as =
an empty schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schem=
a-core#section-10.3.2.4-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-11">
      <h2 id=3D"name-a-vocabulary-for-unevaluate">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">11. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-a-vocabulary-for-unevaluate" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">A Vocabulary for Unevaluated Locations</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-11-1">
                The purpose of these keywords is to enable schema authors t=
o apply
                subschemas to array items or object properties that have no=
t been
                successfully evaluated against any dynamic-scope subschema =
of any
                adjacent keywords.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/=
2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11-2">
                These instance items or properties may have been unsuccessf=
ully evaluated
                against one or more adjacent keyword subschemas, such as wh=
en an assertion
                in a branch of an "anyOf" fails.  Such failed evaluations a=
re not considered
                to contribute to whether or not the item or property has be=
en evaluated.
                Only successful evaluations are considered.<a href=3D"https=
://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11-2" class=3D"pi=
lcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11-3">
                If an item in an array or an object property is "successful=
ly evaluated", it
                is logically considered to be valid in terms of the represe=
ntation of the
                object or array that's expected. For example if a subschema=
 represents a car,
                which requires between 2-4 wheels, and the value of "wheels=
" is 6, the instance
                object is not "evaluated" to be a car, and the "wheels" pro=
perty is considered
                "unevaluated (successfully as a known thing)", and does not=
 retain any annotations.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#section-11-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11-4">
                Recall that adjacent keywords are keywords within the same =
schema object,
                and that the dynamic-scope subschemas include reference tar=
gets as well as
                lexical subschemas.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft=
/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11-5">
                The behavior of these keywords depend on the annotation res=
ults of
                adjacent keywords that apply to the instance location being=
 validated.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-cor=
e#section-11-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11-6">
                Meta-schemas that do not use "$vocabulary" SHOULD be consid=
ered to
                require this vocabulary as if its URI were present with a v=
alue of true.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-c=
ore#section-11-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11-7">
                The current URI for this vocabulary, known as the Unevaluat=
ed Applicator
                vocabulary, is:
                &lt;https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/vocab/unevaluated=
&gt;.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-11-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11-8">
                The current URI for the corresponding meta-schema is:
                <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/meta=
/unevaluated">https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/meta/unevaluated</a></s=
pan>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-11-8" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-11.1">
        <h3 id=3D"name-keyword-independence-2">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
1.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">11.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keyword-independence-2" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">Keyword Independence</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-11.1-1">
                    Schema keywords typically operate independently, withou=
t
                    affecting each other's outcomes. However, the keywords =
in this
                    vocabulary are notable exceptions:<a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.1-1" class=3D"pilcr=
ow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-11.1-2.1">
                            "unevaluatedItems", whose behavior is defined i=
n terms of annotations
                            from "prefixItems", "items", "contains", and it=
self<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-11.1-2.1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-11.1-2.2">
                            "unevaluatedProperties", whose behavior is defi=
ned in terms of
                            annotations from "properties", "patternProperti=
es",
                            "additionalProperties" and itself<a href=3D"htt=
ps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.1-2.2" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
        </ul>
</section>
<div id=3D"unevaluatedItems">
<section id=3D"section-11.2">
        <h3 id=3D"name-unevaluateditems">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
1.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">11.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-unevaluateditems" class=3D"sect=
ion-name selfRef">unevaluatedItems</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-11.2-1">
                    The value of "unevaluatedItems" MUST be a valid JSON Sc=
hema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-11.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.2-2">
                    The behavior of this keyword depends on the annotation =
results of
                    adjacent keywords that apply to the instance location b=
eing validated.
                    Specifically, the annotations from "prefixItems", "item=
s", and "contains",
                    which can come from those keywords when they are adjace=
nt to the
                    "unevaluatedItems" keyword. Those three annotations, as=
 well as
                    "unevaluatedItems", can also result from any and all ad=
jacent
                    <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/=
json-schema-core#in-place" class=3D"xref">in-place applicator</a> (<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#in-place" class=
=3D"xref">Section 10.2</a>)</span> keywords.
                    This includes but is not limited to the in-place applic=
ators
                    defined in this document.<a href=3D"https://json-schema=
.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.2-3">
                    If no relevant annotations are present, the "unevaluate=
dItems"
                    subschema MUST be applied to all locations in the array=
.
                    If a boolean true value is present from any of the rele=
vant annotations,
                    "unevaluatedItems" MUST be ignored.  Otherwise, the sub=
schema
                    MUST be applied to any index greater than the largest a=
nnotation
                    value for "prefixItems", which does not appear in any a=
nnotation
                    value for "contains".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org=
/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a=
></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.2-4">
                    This means that "prefixItems", "items", "contains", and=
 all in-place
                    applicators MUST be evaluated before this keyword can b=
e evaluated.
                    Authors of extension keywords MUST NOT define an in-pla=
ce applicator
                    that would need to be evaluated after this keyword.<a h=
ref=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.2-=
4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.2-5">
                    If the "unevaluatedItems" subschema is applied to any
                    positions within the instance array, it produces an
                    annotation result of boolean true, analogous to the
                    behavior of "items".
                    This annotation affects the behavior of "unevaluatedIte=
ms" in parent schemas.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#section-11.2-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.2-6">
                    Omitting this keyword has the same assertion behavior a=
s
                    an empty schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draf=
t/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.2-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"unevaluatedProperties">
<section id=3D"section-11.3">
        <h3 id=3D"name-unevaluatedproperties">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
1.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">11.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-unevaluatedproperties" class=3D=
"section-name selfRef">unevaluatedProperties</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-11.3-1">
                    The value of "unevaluatedProperties" MUST be a valid JS=
ON Schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-11.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.3-2">
                    The behavior of this keyword depends on the annotation =
results of
                    adjacent keywords that apply to the instance location b=
eing validated.
                    Specifically, the annotations from "properties", "patte=
rnProperties",
                    and "additionalProperties", which can come from those k=
eywords when
                    they are adjacent to the "unevaluatedProperties" keywor=
d.  Those
                    three annotations, as well as "unevaluatedProperties", =
can also
                    result from any and all adjacent
                    <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/=
json-schema-core#in-place" class=3D"xref">in-place applicator</a> (<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#in-place" class=
=3D"xref">Section 10.2</a>)</span> keywords.
                    This includes but is not limited to the in-place applic=
ators
                    defined in this document.<a href=3D"https://json-schema=
.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.3-3">
                    Validation with "unevaluatedProperties" applies only to=
 the child
                    values of instance names that do not appear in the "pro=
perties",
                    "patternProperties", "additionalProperties", or
                    "unevaluatedProperties" annotation results that apply t=
o the
                    instance location being validated.<a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.3-3" class=3D"pilcr=
ow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.3-4">
                    For all such properties, validation succeeds if the chi=
ld instance
                    validates against the "unevaluatedProperties" schema.<a=
 href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.=
3-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.3-5">
                    This means that "properties", "patternProperties", "add=
itionalProperties",
                    and all in-place applicators MUST be evaluated before t=
his keyword can
                    be evaluated.  Authors of extension keywords MUST NOT d=
efine an in-place
                    applicator that would need to be evaluated after this k=
eyword.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-11.3-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.3-6">
                    The annotation result of this keyword is the set of ins=
tance
                    property names validated by this keyword's subschema.
                    This annotation affects the behavior of "unevaluatedPro=
perties" in parent schemas.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12=
/json-schema-core#section-11.3-6" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-11.3-7">
                    Omitting this keyword has the same assertion behavior a=
s
                    an empty schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draf=
t/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-11.3-7" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
</section>
<div id=3D"output">
<section id=3D"section-12">
      <h2 id=3D"name-output-formatting">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-output-formatting" class=3D"section=
-name selfRef">Output Formatting</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-12-1">
                JSON Schema is defined to be platform-independent.  As such=
, to increase compatibility
                across platforms, implementations SHOULD conform to a stand=
ard validation output
                format.  This section describes the minimum requirements th=
at consumers will need to
                properly interpret validation results.<a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12-1" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-12.1">
        <h3 id=3D"name-format">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-format" class=3D"section-name s=
elfRef">Format</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-12.1-1">
                    JSON Schema output is defined using the JSON Schema dat=
a instance model as described
                    in section 4.2.1.  Implementations MAY deviate from thi=
s as supported by their
                    specific languages and platforms, however it is RECOMME=
NDED that the output be
                    convertible to the JSON format defined herein via seria=
lization or other means.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/js=
on-schema-core#section-12.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.2">
        <h3 id=3D"name-output-formats">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-output-formats" class=3D"sectio=
n-name selfRef">Output Formats</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-12.2-1">
                    This specification defines four output formats.  See th=
e "Output Structure"
                    section for the requirements of each format.<a href=3D"=
https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.2-1" clas=
s=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.2-2.1">
                            Flag - A boolean which simply indicates the ove=
rall validation result
                            with no further details.<a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.2-2.1" class=3D"pilcr=
ow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.2-2.2">
                            Basic - Provides validation information in a fl=
at list structure.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sch=
ema-core#section-12.2-2.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.2-2.3">
                            Detailed - Provides validation information in a=
 condensed hierarchical
                            structure based on the structure of the schema.=
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.2-2.3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.2-2.4">
                            Verbose - Provides validation information in an=
 uncondensed hierarchical
                            structure that matches the exact structure of t=
he schema.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-12.2-2.4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
        </ul>
<p id=3D"section-12.2-3">
                    An implementation SHOULD provide at least one of the "f=
lag", "basic", or "detailed"
                    format and MAY provide the "verbose" format.  If it pro=
vides one or more of the
                    "detailed" or "verbose" formats, it MUST also provide t=
he "flag" format.
                    Implementations SHOULD specify in their documentation w=
hich formats they support.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/=
json-schema-core#section-12.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.3">
        <h3 id=3D"name-minimum-information">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-minimum-information" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">Minimum Information</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-12.3-1">
                    Beyond the simplistic "flag" output, additional informa=
tion is useful to aid in
                    debugging a schema or instance.  Each sub-result SHOULD=
 contain the information
                    contained within this section at a minimum.<a href=3D"h=
ttps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.3-1" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.3-2">
                    A single object that contains all of these components i=
s considered an
                    output unit.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/20=
20-12/json-schema-core#section-12.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.3-3">
                    Implementations MAY elect to provide additional informa=
tion.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-12.3-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-12.3.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-keyword-relative-location">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.3.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.3.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keyword-relative-location" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Keyword Relative Location</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.1-1">
                        The relative location of the validating keyword tha=
t follows the validation
                        path.  The value MUST be expressed as a JSON Pointe=
r, and it MUST include
                        any by-reference applicators such as "$ref" or "$dy=
namicRef".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core=
#section-12.3.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-12.3.1-2">
<pre>
/properties/width/$ref/minimum

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-12.3.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.1-3">
                    Note that this pointer may not be resolvable by the nor=
mal JSON Pointer process
                    due to the inclusion of these by-reference applicator k=
eywords.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
ection-12.3.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.1-4">
                        The JSON key for this information is "keywordLocati=
on".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-12.3.1-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.3.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-keyword-absolute-location">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.3.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.3.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-keyword-absolute-location" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Keyword Absolute Location</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.2-1">
                        The absolute, dereferenced location of the validati=
ng keyword.  The value MUST
                        be expressed as a full URI using the canonical URI =
of the relevant schema resource
                        with a JSON Pointer fragment, and it MUST NOT inclu=
de by-reference applicators
                        such as "$ref" or "$dynamicRef" as non-terminal pat=
h components.
                        It MAY end in such keywords if the error or annotat=
ion is for that
                        keyword, such as an unresolvable reference.
                        <span class=3D"cref">
                            Note that "absolute" here is in the sense of "a=
bsolute filesystem path"
                            (meaning the complete location) rather than the=
 "absolute-URI"
                            terminology from RFC 3986 (meaning with scheme =
but without fragment).
                            Keyword absolute locations will have a fragment=
 in order to
                            identify the keyword.
            </span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-sc=
hema-core#section-12.3.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-12.3.2-2">
<pre>
https://example.com/schemas/common#/$defs/count/minimum

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-12.3.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.2-3">
                        This information MAY be omitted only if either the =
dynamic scope did not pass
                        over a reference or if the schema does not declare =
an absolute URI as its "$id".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-=
12/json-schema-core#section-12.3.2-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.2-4">
                        The JSON key for this information is "absoluteKeywo=
rdLocation".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-12.3.2-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.3.3">
          <h4 id=3D"name-instance-location">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.3.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.3.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-instance-location" class=3D=
"section-name selfRef">Instance Location</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.3-1">
                        The location of the JSON value within the instance =
being validated.  The
                        value MUST be expressed as a JSON Pointer.<a href=
=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.3.3-1=
" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.3-2">
                        The JSON key for this information is "instanceLocat=
ion".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sect=
ion-12.3.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.3.4">
          <h4 id=3D"name-error-or-annotation">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.3.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.3.4. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-error-or-annotation" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">Error or Annotation</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.4-1">
                        The error or annotation that is produced by the val=
idation.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#s=
ection-12.3.4-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.4-2">
                        For errors, the specific wording for the message is=
 not defined by this
                        specification.  Implementations will need to provid=
e this.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-12.3.4-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.4-3">
                        For annotations, each keyword that produces an anno=
tation specifies its
                        format.  By default, it is the keyword's value.<a h=
ref=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.3.=
4-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.4-4">
                        The JSON key for failed validations is "error"; for=
 successful validations
                        it is "annotation".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.o=
rg/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.3.4-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.3.5">
          <h4 id=3D"name-nested-results">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.3.5" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.3.5. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-nested-results" class=3D"se=
ction-name selfRef">Nested Results</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.5-1">
                        For the two hierarchical structures, this property =
will hold nested errors
                        and annotations.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/=
draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.3.5-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</=
a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.3.5-2">
                        The JSON key for nested results in failed validatio=
ns is "errors"; for
                        successful validations it is "annotations".  Note t=
he plural forms, as
                        a keyword with nested results can also have a local=
 error or annotation.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-=
schema-core#section-12.3.5-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.4">
        <h3 id=3D"name-output-structure">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.4. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-output-structure" class=3D"sect=
ion-name selfRef">Output Structure</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-12.4-1">
                    The output MUST be an object containing a boolean prope=
rty named "valid".  When
                    additional information about the result is required, th=
e output MUST also contain
                    "errors" or "annotations" as described below.<a href=3D=
"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4-1" cla=
ss=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.4-2.1">
                            "valid" - a boolean value indicating the overal=
l validation success or
                            failure<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft=
/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4-2.1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.4-2.2">
                            "errors" - the collection of errors or annotati=
ons produced by a failed
                            validation<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/dr=
aft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4-2.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.4-2.3">
                            "annotations" - the collection of errors or ann=
otations produced by a
                            successful validation<a href=3D"https://json-sc=
hema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4-2.3" class=3D"pilcrow"=
>=C2=B6</a>
</li>
        </ul>
<p id=3D"section-12.4-3">
                    For these examples, the following schema and instance w=
ill be used.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-12.4-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-12.4-4">
<pre>
{
  "$id": "https://example.com/polygon",
  "$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
  "$defs": {
    "point": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "x": { "type": "number" },
        "y": { "type": "number" }
      },
      "additionalProperties": false,
      "required": [ "x", "y" ]
    }
  },
  "type": "array",
  "items": { "$ref": "#/$defs/point" },
  "minItems": 3
}

[
  {
    "x": 2.5,
    "y": 1.3
  },
  {
    "x": 1,
    "z": 6.7
  }
]

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-12.4-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-12.4-5">
                    This instance will fail validation and produce errors, =
but it's trivial to deduce
                    examples for passing schemas that produce annotations.<=
a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12=
.4-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.4-6">
                    Specifically, the errors it will produce are:<a href=3D=
"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4-6" cla=
ss=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.4-7.1">
                            The second object is missing a "y" property.<a =
href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4=
-7.1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.4-7.2">
                            The second object has a disallowed "z" property=
.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-=
12.4-7.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.4-7.3">
                            There are only two objects, but three are requi=
red.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#secti=
on-12.4-7.3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
        </ul>
<p id=3D"section-12.4-8">
                    Note that the error message wording as depicted in thes=
e examples is not a
                    requirement of this specification.  Implementations SHO=
ULD craft error messages
                    tailored for their audience or provide a templating mec=
hanism that allows their
                    users to craft their own messages.<a href=3D"https://js=
on-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4-8" class=3D"pilcr=
ow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<section id=3D"section-12.4.1">
          <h4 id=3D"name-flag">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.4.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.4.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-flag" class=3D"section-name=
 selfRef">Flag</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.1-1">
                        In the simplest case, merely the boolean result for=
 the "valid" valid property
                        needs to be fulfilled.<a href=3D"https://json-schem=
a.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=
=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-12.4.1-2">
<pre>
{
  "valid": false
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-12.4.1-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.1-3">
                        Because no errors or annotations are returned with =
this format, it is
                        RECOMMENDED that implementations use short-circuiti=
ng logic to return
                        failure or success as soon as the outcome can be de=
termined.  For example,
                        if an "anyOf" keyword contains five sub-schemas, an=
d the second one
                        passes, there is no need to check the other three. =
 The logic can simply
                        return with success.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4.1-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=
=B6</a></p>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.4.2">
          <h4 id=3D"name-basic">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.4.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.4.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-basic" class=3D"section-nam=
e selfRef">Basic</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.2-1">
                        The "Basic" structure is a flat list of output unit=
s.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-12.4.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-12.4.2-2">
<pre>
{
  "valid": false,
  "errors": [
    {
      "keywordLocation": "",
      "instanceLocation": "",
      "error": "A subschema had errors."
    },
    {
      "keywordLocation": "/items/$ref",
      "absoluteKeywordLocation":
        "https://example.com/polygon#/$defs/point",
      "instanceLocation": "/1",
      "error": "A subschema had errors."
    },
    {
      "keywordLocation": "/items/$ref/required",
      "absoluteKeywordLocation":
        "https://example.com/polygon#/$defs/point/required",
      "instanceLocation": "/1",
      "error": "Required property 'y' not found."
    },
    {
      "keywordLocation": "/items/$ref/additionalProperties",
      "absoluteKeywordLocation":
        "https://example.com/polygon#/$defs/point/additionalProperties",
      "instanceLocation": "/1/z",
      "error": "Additional property 'z' found but was invalid."
    },
    {
      "keywordLocation": "/minItems",
      "instanceLocation": "",
      "error": "Expected at least 3 items but found 2"
    }
  ]
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-12.4.2-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.4.3">
          <h4 id=3D"name-detailed">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.4.3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.4.3. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-detailed" class=3D"section-=
name selfRef">Detailed</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.3-1">
                        The "Detailed" structure is based on the schema and=
 can be more readable
                        for both humans and machines.  Having the structure=
 organized this way makes
                        associations between the errors more apparent.  For=
 example, the fact that
                        the missing "y" property and the extra "z" property=
 both stem from the same
                        location in the instance is not immediately obvious=
 in the "Basic" structure.
                        In a hierarchy, the correlation is more easily iden=
tified.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-12.4.3-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.3-2">
                        The following rules govern the construction of the =
results object:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema=
-core#section-12.4.3-2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.4.3-3.1">
                                All applicator keywords ("*Of", "$ref", "if=
"/"then"/"else", etc.) require
                                a node.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/d=
raft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4.3-3.1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6<=
/a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.4.3-3.2">
                                Nodes that have no children are removed.<a =
href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4=
.3-3.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
            <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-12.4.3-3.3">
                                Nodes that have a single child are replaced=
 by the child.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-=
core#section-12.4.3-3.3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          </ul>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.3-4">
                        Branch nodes do not require an error message or an =
annotation.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-cor=
e#section-12.4.3-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-12.4.3-5">
<pre>
{
  "valid": false,
  "keywordLocation": "",
  "instanceLocation": "",
  "errors": [
    {
      "valid": false,
      "keywordLocation": "/items/$ref",
      "absoluteKeywordLocation":
        "https://example.com/polygon#/$defs/point",
      "instanceLocation": "/1",
      "errors": [
        {
          "valid": false,
          "keywordLocation": "/items/$ref/required",
          "absoluteKeywordLocation":
            "https://example.com/polygon#/$defs/point/required",
          "instanceLocation": "/1",
          "error": "Required property 'y' not found."
        },
        {
          "valid": false,
          "keywordLocation": "/items/$ref/additionalProperties",
          "absoluteKeywordLocation":
            "https://example.com/polygon#/$defs/point/additionalProperties"=
,
          "instanceLocation": "/1/z",
          "error": "Additional property 'z' found but was invalid."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "valid": false,
      "keywordLocation": "/minItems",
      "instanceLocation": "",
      "error": "Expected at least 3 items but found 2"
    }
  ]
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-12.4.3-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.4.4">
          <h4 id=3D"name-verbose">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.4.4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.4.4. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-verbose" class=3D"section-n=
ame selfRef">Verbose</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.4-1">
                        The "Verbose" structure is a fully realized hierarc=
hy that exactly matches
                        that of the schema.  This structure has application=
s in form generation and
                        validation where the error's location is important.=
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.4.4-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.4-2">
                        The primary difference between this and the "Detail=
ed" structure is that
                        all results are returned.  This includes sub-schema=
 validation results that
                        would otherwise be removed (e.g. annotations for fa=
iled validations,
                        successful validations inside a `not` keyword, etc.=
).  Because of this, it
                        is RECOMMENDED that each node also carry a `valid` =
property to indicate the
                        validation result for that node.<a href=3D"https://=
json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-12.4.4-2" class=3D"p=
ilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.4-3">
                        Because this output structure can be quite large, a=
 smaller example is given
                        here for brevity.  The URI of the full output struc=
ture of the example above is:
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/output/verbose-example">https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/output/ve=
rbose-example</a></span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/j=
son-schema-core#section-12.4.4-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<div class=3D"alignLeft art-text artwork" id=3D"section-12.4.4-4">
<pre>
// schema
{
  "$id": "https://example.com/polygon",
  "$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "validProp": true,
  },
  "additionalProperties": false
}

// instance
{
  "validProp": 5,
  "disallowedProp": "value"
}

// result
{
  "valid": false,
  "keywordLocation": "",
  "instanceLocation": "",
  "errors": [
    {
      "valid": true,
      "keywordLocation": "/type",
      "instanceLocation": ""
    },
    {
      "valid": true,
      "keywordLocation": "/properties",
      "instanceLocation": ""
    },
    {
      "valid": false,
      "keywordLocation": "/additionalProperties",
      "instanceLocation": "",
      "errors": [
        {
          "valid": false,
          "keywordLocation": "/additionalProperties",
          "instanceLocation": "/disallowedProp",
          "error": "Additional property 'disallowedProp' found but was inva=
lid."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}

</pre><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#sec=
tion-12.4.4-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-12.4.5">
          <h4 id=3D"name-output-validation-schemas">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
2.4.5" class=3D"section-number selfRef">12.4.5. </a><a href=3D"https://json=
-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-output-validation-schemas" =
class=3D"section-name selfRef">Output validation schemas</a>
          </h4>
<p id=3D"section-12.4.5-1">
                        For convenience, JSON Schema has been provided to v=
alidate output generated
                        by implementations.  Its URI is:
                        <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020=
-12/output/schema">https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/output/schema</a><=
/span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#se=
ction-12.4.5-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</section>
</section>
</div>
<div id=3D"security">
<section id=3D"section-13">
      <h2 id=3D"name-security-considerations">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
3" class=3D"section-number selfRef">13. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-security-considerations" class=3D"s=
ection-name selfRef">Security Considerations</a>
      </h2>
<p id=3D"section-13-1">
                Both schemas and instances are JSON values. As such, all se=
curity considerations
                defined in <span><a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2=
020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8259" class=3D"xref">RFC 8259</a> [<a href=3D"ht=
tps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8259" class=3D"xref=
">RFC8259</a>]</span> apply.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#section-13-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-13-2">
                Instances and schemas are both frequently written by untrus=
ted third parties, to be
                deployed on public Internet servers.
                Validators should take care that the parsing and validating=
 against schemas does not consume excessive
                system resources.
                Validators MUST NOT fall into an infinite loop.<a href=3D"h=
ttps://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-13-2" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-13-3">
                A malicious party could cause an implementation to repeated=
ly collect a copy
                of a very large value as an annotation.  Implementations SH=
OULD guard against
                excessive consumption of system resources in such a scenari=
o.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section=
-13-3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-13-4">
                Servers MUST ensure that malicious parties cannot change th=
e functionality of
                existing schemas by uploading a schema with a pre-existing =
or very similar "$id".<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#section-13-4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-13-5">
                Individual JSON Schema vocabularies are liable to also have=
 their own security
                considerations. Consult the respective specifications for m=
ore information.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schem=
a-core#section-13-5" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-13-6">
                Schema authors should take care with "$comment" contents, a=
s a malicious
                implementation can display them to end-users in violation o=
f a spec, or
                fail to strip them if such behavior is expected.<a href=3D"=
https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-13-6" class=
=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<p id=3D"section-13-7">
                A malicious schema author could place executable code or ot=
her dangerous
                material within a "$comment".  Implementations MUST NOT par=
se or otherwise
                take action based on "$comment" contents.<a href=3D"https:/=
/json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-13-7" class=3D"pilc=
row">=C2=B6</a></p>
</section>
</div>
<section id=3D"section-14">
      <h2 id=3D"name-iana-considerations">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
4" class=3D"section-number selfRef">14. </a><a href=3D"https://json-schema.=
org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-iana-considerations" class=3D"secti=
on-name selfRef">IANA Considerations</a>
      </h2>
<section id=3D"section-14.1">
        <h3 id=3D"name-application-schemajson">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
4.1" class=3D"section-number selfRef">14.1. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-application-schemajson" class=
=3D"section-name selfRef">application/schema+json</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-14.1-1">
                    The proposed MIME media type for JSON Schema is defined=
 as follows:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-14.1-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.1-2.1">Type name: application=
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
4.1-2.1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.1-2.2">Subtype name=
: schema+json<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-c=
ore#section-14.1-2.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.1-2.3">Required par=
ameters: N/A<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-14.1-2.3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.1-2.4">
                            Encoding considerations: Encoding consideration=
s are
                            identical to those specified for the "applicati=
on/json"
                            media type.  See <span><a href=3D"https://json-=
schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8259" class=3D"xref">JSON</a> =
[<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#RFC8259"=
 class=3D"xref">RFC8259</a>]</span>.<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draf=
t/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-14.1-2.4" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.1-2.5">
                            Security considerations: See Section
                            <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#security" class=3D"xref">13</a> above.<a href=3D"https:/=
/json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-14.1-2.5" class=3D"=
pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.1-2.6">
                            Interoperability considerations: See Sections
                            <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#language" class=3D"xref">6.2</a>,
                            <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#integers" class=3D"xref">6.3</a>, and
                            <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#regex" class=3D"xref">6.4</a> above.<a href=3D"https://j=
son-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-14.1-2.6" class=3D"pi=
lcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.1-2.7">
                            Fragment identifier considerations: See Section
                            <a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-1=
2/json-schema-core#fragments" class=3D"xref">5</a><a href=3D"https://json-s=
chema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-14.1-2.7" class=3D"pilcrow=
">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
        </ul>
</section>
<section id=3D"section-14.2">
        <h3 id=3D"name-application-schema-instance">
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
4.2" class=3D"section-number selfRef">14.2. </a><a href=3D"https://json-sch=
ema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#name-application-schema-instance" cl=
ass=3D"section-name selfRef">application/schema-instance+json</a>
        </h3>
<p id=3D"section-14.2-1">
                    The proposed MIME media type for JSON Schema Instances =
that require
                    a JSON Schema-specific media type is defined as follows=
:<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-=
14.2-1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a></p>
<ul class=3D"normal ulEmpty">
<li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.2-2.1">Type name: application=
<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-core#section-1=
4.2-2.1" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.2-2.2">Subtype name=
: schema-instance+json<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json=
-schema-core#section-14.2-2.2" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.2-2.3">Required par=
ameters: N/A<a href=3D"https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/json-schema-co=
re#section-14.2-2.3" class=3D"pilcrow">=C2=B6</a>
</li>
          <li class=3D"normal ulEmpty" id=3D"section-14.2-2.4">
                            Encoding considerations: Encoding consideration=
s are
                            identical to those specified for the "applicati=
on/json"
